- id: INFRA-1454
  domain: INFRA
  title: "EFFECTIVE: containerize agent bash execution per worktree"
  status: done
  priority: P1
  effort: l
  description: |
    Commercial-launch precondition surfaced by Persona-5 skeptic validation interview (see docs/strategy/commercial/COMMERCIAL_PIVOT_SPARRING.md). Today agents run bash directly on the host filesystem inside a linked git worktree. Trust model collapses into 'operator owns the machine' — defensible for solo dogfood, NOT defensible for any environment where the agent ingests third-party content or where the operator wouldn't run a curl|bash from a stranger. A single adversarial dependency-description-interpreted-as-instruction = CVE with Jeff's name on it. This is ship-blocker for any commercial tier, not a Growth-tier feature.
  acceptance_criteria:
    - Agents executing bash inside a claimed worktree run inside an unprivileged container runtime (Docker / podman / macOS sandbox-exec) not the host shell
    - Container has read-write access only to the worktree directory; cannot reach host filesystem outside it
    - Container has no host-network access beyond an explicit allowlist (configured LLM API endpoint, configured registries)
    - chump fleet doctor reports sandbox-runtime status (active / missing / misconfigured) and exits non-zero on missing
    - Fallback no-sandbox mode (current behavior) requires explicit --unsafe-host-exec flag with operator-acknowledged warning
    - "CI test: spawn agent in sandbox, attempt host-fs escape (write to ~/, read /etc/passwd, bind external port), verify all fail"
    - "Onboarding docs updated: sandbox runtime is a prerequisite, not optional"
    - "Port-namespace isolation: each worktree's sandbox gets a deterministic, isolated port namespace; multiple worktrees running the same docker-compose stack do not collide on port 5432/6379/etc — container-network bridge per worktree with internal-only DNS for service discovery within that worktree"
    - "CI test: spawn 5 parallel worktrees each running an identical docker-compose with hardcoded port 5432; verify all 5 reach steady state without port-bind conflicts"
  closed_date: '2026-05-24'
  closed_pr: 2350
  outcome_id: MISSION-010

- id: INFRA-1455
  domain: INFRA
  title: "EFFECTIVE: chump rollup --semantic for fan-out PR consolidation"
  status: done
  priority: P1
  effort: m
  description: |
    Commercial-launch precondition surfaced by Persona-5 skeptic validation interview (see docs/strategy/commercial/COMMERCIAL_PIVOT_SPARRING.md). The $49/operator/month Team tier sells on symmetric fan-out (one architectural intent → N services). Today when N agents finish, the operator sees N PRs — a firehose that clogs CI allocation and forces micro-review. Skeptic verdict: 'If my reward is a 40-PR firehose I will uninstall within 72 hours.' This is the actual commercial premise. Without it, Chump is a script that opens N terminal tabs, not an orchestrator.
  acceptance_criteria:
    - New chump rollup <epic-id> [--semantic] command groups PRs from sub-gaps under one parent epic
    - Clusters patches by file-touched + AC-satisfied + structural diff similarity into named 'strategy classes'
    - "Output: 'N PRs converged on Strategy A (file list, diff signature), M on Strategy B (diff), K blocked (reason)'"
    - Cockpit (chump --web) renders the rollup as a reviewable surface with side-by-side strategy diffs
    - chump rollup accept-strategy <name> merges all PRs in that strategy class as one operator decision
    - "Symmetric fan-out test fixture: spawn N agents against N test microservices doing the same dep upgrade, verify rollup converges to expected strategy classes"
    - "Asymmetric fallback: when no clustering signal exists (e.g. unrelated backlog), rollup degrades to flat PR list with no false-strategy claims"
  closed_date: '2026-05-22'
  closed_pr: 2352
  outcome_id: MISSION-010

- id: INFRA-1456
  domain: INFRA
  title: "EFFECTIVE: chump inspect/resume/scrap eject-and-inspect primitive"
  status: done
  priority: P1
  effort: m
  description: |
    Commercial-launch precondition surfaced by Persona-5 skeptic validation interview (see docs/strategy/commercial/COMMERCIAL_PIVOT_SPARRING.md). The Saturday-morning-uninstall scenario: 20-agent fleet runs Friday night, 18 green / 2 wedged. If operator can't tell why those 2 are wedged in under 60 seconds, the entire Chump abstraction becomes net-negative — operator is debugging Chump instead of their codebase. Skeptic verdict: 'I am not going to be a Chump administrator.' Eject-and-inspect must make a wedged agent feel like debugging a normal local git branch.
  acceptance_criteria:
    - "chump inspect <gap-id> opens a tmux session with 3 panes: worktree shell (cd'd in), tail -f of ambient.jsonl filtered to this gap, last N agent bash commands with cmd+cwd+exit+stdout-tail"
    - "Trajectory capture: every agent bash invocation per gap logged with structured fields (timestamp, cmd, cwd, exit_code, stdout_tail) to queryable structured log"
    - chump resume <gap-id> reattaches a wedged gap to fleet rotation after manual operator fix (validates worktree state + commit graph + re-leases atomically)
    - chump scrap <gap-id> cleanly destroys worktree directory, kills any associated sandbox container, releases lease, leaves zero host-fs/disk-port/container residue
    - INFRA-779 gitdir-confusion recovery path documented under chump inspect (auto-repair attempt + manual fallback command shown)
    - "CI test: wedge an agent intentionally (kill -9 mid-run), run inspect, verify all 3 panes populated with the right state"
    - "CI test: chump scrap on a wedged gap leaves zero residue (no orphan worktree dir, no orphan container, no orphan lease, no bound ports)"
  closed_date: '2026-05-24'
  closed_pr: 2351
  outcome_id: MISSION-010

- id: INFRA-1457
  domain: INFRA
  title: "RESILIENT: transitive-import lease auto-expansion at claim time"
  status: open
  priority: P1
  effort: m
  description: |
    Architectural gap surfaced by Persona-5 critique of Q1 (state sync) in commercial validation interview. Today chump claim --paths is operator-supplied: agent A claims utility.rs, agent B claims consumer.rs which transitively imports utility.rs but didn't declare it. B's working AST goes stale the moment A commits. We detect this REACTIVELY via hot_file_collision in ambient.jsonl. We should detect it PREVENTIVELY at claim time via static import-graph expansion. Without this, the 'voluntary cooperation' framing is true and is a real liability under fan-out load.
  acceptance_criteria:
    - chump claim <gap-id> --paths X,Y auto-expands lease to include transitive consumers of X,Y
    - Static import-graph computed per-language (Rust crate deps from cargo metadata, JS/TS imports from AST, Python imports from AST) for the active repo
    - Two agents cannot both claim if expanded path sets overlap — atomic CAS at state.db rejects the second claim
    - Operator override --no-transitive-paths supported (logged + warning emitted)
    - hot_file_collision event remains as backstop for genuinely-missed transitive deps (dynamic imports, reflection, etc.)
    - "Test fixture: agent A claims src/utility.rs, agent B attempts to claim src/consumer.rs which imports utility.rs, second claim fails atomically with clear error"
    - "Performance: import-graph cached, expansion adds < 200ms to chump claim latency on a 100kLOC repo"
  outcome_id: MISSION-010

