- id: INFRA-1475
  domain: INFRA
  title: "EFFECTIVE: centralized cross-operator fleet queue for team coordination"
  status: done
  priority: P1
  effort: l
  description: |
    Team-tier ($49/operator/month) headline feature missed in 2026-05-15 audit pass. Persona-1 (Marcus) named this as the second reason to swipe the Team-tier card: 'Even though execution happens locally, the coordination is unified. If I have a beefy local cluster sitting under my desk or a designated team neural-farm machine in the office, we can queue up massive parallel jobs without choking our individual laptops.' Today state.db is single-operator and NATS push tier (FLEET-034) handles single-fleet routing. The cross-operator team queue — multiple humans queueing work into one shared fleet — is unspecified.
  acceptance_criteria:
    - Multiple operators on the same team share one logical work queue; gaps reserved by operator A are visible to operator B's fleet view
    - "Cross-operator atomic claim: only one operator's worker can claim a given gap; CAS rejects the other"
    - Team-scoped state.db (or equivalent) hosted at a single location operators point their workers at; CHUMP_TEAM_STATE_URL or similar
    - "Worker capability advertising: workers running on operator A's hardware can claim gaps reserved by operator B if skills/machine routing matches"
    - chump --web cockpit shows fleet activity across all operators on the team, not just the local machine's workers
    - "Quotas per operator: spend-cap predecessor; operator A can't accidentally exhaust the team's compute budget on one runaway fleet"
    - "Offline degradation: if the team-queue endpoint is unreachable, individual operators fall back to local state.db without data loss; sync on reconnect"
    - "CI test: 3-operator simulated team, each queueing work, verify atomic claim + cross-visibility + offline fallback"
