- id: INFRA-1588
  domain: INFRA
  title: "RESILIENT: pre-push hook SIGPIPE on worktree-list awk produces silent failure (exit 141, no diagnostic)"
  status: done
  priority: P1
  effort: s
  acceptance_criteria:
    - "Fix the SIGPIPE in .git/hooks/pre-push line ~751 where 'git worktree list --porcelain "
    - " awk /^worktree/{print $2;exit}' produces exit 141 under set -o pipefail because awk closes pipe early. Preferred fix: read git worktree output into a variable first then parse (no pipeline = no SIGPIPE)."
    - "Audit remaining hook for similar 'cmd "
    - " head -1' / 'cmd "
    - " awk ...exit' constructs under set -o pipefail; refactor each to pipeline-free form."
    - "Add ERR trap to hook: 'trap \"echo [pre-push] hook aborted at line $LINENO with exit $?\" ERR' so operator sees the failing line + exit code BEFORE silent abort. Trap placed AFTER set -e/-o pipefail so it actually fires."
    - "Regression test scripts/ci/test-pre-push-hook-no-sigpipe.sh: in a temp worktree, run the hook directly with stub env (CHUMP_BYPASS_BOT_MERGE=1, Bot-Merge-Bypass: trailer), assert exit 0 AND that stdout/stderr contain expected progress markers (no silent abort)."
    - "Bonus: the hook's existing 'failed to push' error message must be augmented with the captured line+exit from the ERR trap when running in a CI/scripted context."
    - "Cross-link: 2026-05-16 INFRA-1539 ship (#2250) hit this — required workaround 'git -c core.hooksPath=/dev/null push --force-with-lease' which is unsafe (bypasses ALL hooks, not just the buggy line). Also confirmed reproducible on INFRA-1541 #2251 and INFRA-1580 #2252 ship attempts in same session."
  notes: |
    Discovered 2026-05-16 while shipping Wave 0 fan-out (INFRA-1539 #2250, INFRA-1541 #2251, INFRA-1580 #2252). All three subagents hit the same silent push failure; the INFRA-1539 subagent diagnosed it to line 751.
    
    Root cause:
      main_repo="$(git worktree list --porcelain 2>/dev/null | awk '/^worktree / {print $2; exit}')"
    
    The awk 'exit' after first match closes its stdin while git is still writing → SIGPIPE on git → under set -o pipefail this becomes exit 141 → silent because the SIGPIPE happens mid-script with no diagnostic.
    
    Three candidate fixes (named in AC). Option 3 (read-into-variable-first) is cleanest because it eliminates the pipeline entirely.
    
    Cost of NOT fixing: every subagent shipping a Wave 1+ gap will hit this. Workaround (CHUMP_GAP_CHECK=0 + --no-verify) bypasses ALL hooks not just this line. Belongs in Wave 0 because every shipping path uses this hook.
  closed_date: '2026-05-17'
  closed_pr: 2257
  outcome_id: MISSION-010

- id: INFRA-1589
  domain: INFRA
  title: "EFFECTIVE: adopt existing AST tools (ast-grep + universal-ctags + rust-analyzer CLI + gh search code) as interim discipline while INFRA-1583 chump-mcp-code is built — runtime-verification before missing-claim, today"
  status: open
  priority: P2
  effort: s
  description: |
    INFRA-1583 (chump-mcp-code MCP server) is 2-3 weeks of work and lives in Phase 5+ of the roadmap. The misdiagnosis pattern (INFRA-1575: A2A claimed missing when shipped) is biting NOW. The 5 tools mentioned in INFRA-1583 design exist as off-the-shelf CLIs today and can be adopted without writing any new code: (1) ast-grep — tree-sitter-based AST-aware structural search, brew-installable, drop-in superior to regex grep for symbol queries; (2) universal-ctags — 5-min setup, produces tags file for O(1) symbol lookup vs O(file-size) grep; (3) rust-analyzer — already in IDE installs, has CLI mode for type/trait queries beyond what tree-sitter can resolve; (4) gh search code <ID> — would have caught the A2A misdiagnosis in ONE CALL (gh search code INFRA-1296 --repo X returns the shipping commit immediately); (5) tree-sitter-cli — zero-deps JSON AST output if scripted access needed. Interim discipline: add allowlist entries + AGENTS.md rule that says "before claiming feature X is missing, run gh search code <X> and ast-grep --pattern \"...\" before filing". The rule is the load-bearing part; the tools make it cheap to follow. Pairs with the prompt-rule integration in INFRA-1583 AC; this gap ships the rule + tool adoption today, INFRA-1583 replaces the CLI invocations with structured MCP calls later.
  acceptance_criteria:
    - scripts/setup/bootstrap-manifest.yaml gains entries for ast-grep + universal-ctags as developer tools (install via brew on macOS, apt/cargo elsewhere); chump-fleet-bootstrap.sh --check warns when missing
    - .claude/settings.local.json or repo-level permissions gain allowlist entries for ast-grep, ctags, gh search code, rust-analyzer invocations so the fleet can use them without approval prompts
    - "AGENTS.md Filing meta-patterns section gains a Runtime verification before missing-claim subsection with the four-check rule: (a) gh search code <ID> for gap/PR history, (b) ast-grep --pattern for symbol existence, (c) test -f / ls for file paths in AC, (d) chump gap list --status done --json for closed-gap lookup; cross-references INFRA-238 and INFRA-1575 as cautionary precedents"
    - docs/process/CLAUDE_GOTCHAS.md gains a Code-intelligence shortcuts subsection listing the canonical command for each of the five common queries (symbol exists, callers, route handler, event emitter, gap history) with copy-paste examples
    - "scripts/dev/verify-existence.sh helper wraps the four-check rule into a single invocation: verify-existence.sh INFRA-1296 runs all four checks and reports a tri-state {confirmed_shipped, confirmed_absent, ambiguous} — agents call this before filing missing-claim gaps"
    - scripts/ci/test-misdiagnosis-prevention-interim.sh replays the A2A scenario using these CLI tools (no MCP server required) and asserts the verify-existence.sh helper returns confirmed_shipped for INFRA-1296
    - When INFRA-1583 chump-mcp-code Phase 1 ships, the verify-existence.sh helper is rewritten to delegate to code.gap_history MCP call; AGENTS.md rule updated to reference MCP tools as primary with CLI as fallback
  notes: |
    wave: 0 (interim runtime-verification discipline — should land alongside Wave 0 truth gates)
  outcome_id: MISSION-010

- id: INFRA-1590
  domain: INFRA
  title: "RESILIENT: PWA design-token discipline pre-commit lint — reject raw hex outside :root, new --*-primary aliases, mismatched var() fallbacks (mirrors Rust-First-Bypass pattern)"
  status: open
  priority: P1
  effort: s
  description: |
    The PWA already has competent design tokens (web/v2/index.html:14-64) for dark/light/high-contrast. But there's no enforcement, so new components route around them:
    
    - web/v2/welcome.js:46-55 invents --bg-primary / --bg-secondary / --accent #7c83fd — a purple that exists nowhere else in the system; canonical accent is #0a84ff.
    - web/v2/cockpit.js redefines var() fallbacks with #0d0d0f / #1a1a1c / #2a2a2e that don't match index.html's #0a0a0a / #141414 / #1e1e1e.
    - New components consistently use --text-primary / --bg-primary as if those are canonical, when the system uses --text / --bg (with --text-secondary / --bg-surface / --bg-elevated).
    
    Without a lint, each new component adds drift. With a lint, future drift is rejected at commit time.
    
    Pattern mirror: META-064 Rust-First gate already lives at scripts/git-hooks/pre-commit-rust-first.sh with a 'Rust-First-Bypass: <reason>' commit-trailer escape valve. Copy that shape exactly.
    
    Rough shape:
    (a) scripts/lint/css-token-discipline.sh — bash + grep/awk, scans staged .html / .js / .css files (git diff --cached --name-only).
    (b) Reject rules (each emits a fix-it line pointing to the canonical token):
        1. Raw hex colors (#[0-9a-fA-F]{3,8}) or rgb()/rgba()/hsl() literals OUTSIDE of :root { } or [data-theme='...'] { } selectors. (Tokens are allowed in their definition; uses must var() them.)
        2. New --*-primary or --*-secondary CSS variable definitions. The canonical names are --text, --text-secondary, --bg, --bg-surface, --bg-elevated, --accent, --accent-dim, --success, --warn, --error, --border, --radius, --radius-sm.
        3. var(--token, FALLBACK) where FALLBACK does not match the token's value in :root. Detection: parse :root values from index.html, scan codebase for var() calls, compare.
        4. Any single color literal appearing in >3 different files (drift detector — catches the first repeat before it becomes a pattern).
    (c) Pre-commit hook wiring: append to scripts/git-hooks/pre-commit chain (or its registered slot). Hook runs only if staged files match web/**/*.{js,html,css}.
    (d) Bypass: 'Token-Discipline-Bypass: <one-sentence reason>' commit trailer. Hook checks the about-to-commit message via git interpret-trailers.
    (e) Audit log: bypasses emit ambient.jsonl event kind=token_discipline_bypass with {commit_sha, reason, files} (mirror Rust-First-Bypass audit).
    (f) Baseline: existing violations (welcome.js, cockpit.js, others) whitelisted at install time via .css-discipline-baseline.txt. CI passes day-one. Cleanup happens via separate gaps (INFRA-1585 onboarding consolidation already deletes the welcome.js violations).
    (g) Smoke test scripts/ci/test-css-token-discipline.sh — runs lint against tests/fixtures/css-token-violation.html and tests/fixtures/css-token-clean.html, asserts the right exit codes.
    (h) docs/process/CSS_TOKEN_DISCIPLINE.md — short page documenting the rules, the canonical token list, and the bypass mechanic. Link from CLAUDE.md 'Hard rules' section.
    
    When picked, decompose into:
      sub-1: the linter + fixture tests
      sub-2: pre-commit hook wiring + bypass mechanic
      sub-3: baseline file + ambient audit emit
      sub-4: docs + CLAUDE.md link
  acceptance_criteria:
    - "scripts/lint/css-token-discipline.sh exists and exits non-zero on raw hex outside :root"
    - Linter rejects new --*-primary or --*-secondary CSS variable definitions
    - "Linter rejects var(--token, FALLBACK) where FALLBACK !== :root value"
    - Linter detects 'color literal appears in >3 files' as drift
    - Pre-commit hook wired into scripts/git-hooks/pre-commit chain
    - "'Token-Discipline-Bypass: <reason>' commit trailer bypasses the gate"
    - Bypass emits kind=token_discipline_bypass to ambient.jsonl with {commit_sha, reason, files}
    - .css-discipline-baseline.txt whitelists existing violations so CI passes at install
    - scripts/ci/test-css-token-discipline.sh round-trips linter against clean + dirty fixtures
    - docs/process/CSS_TOKEN_DISCIPLINE.md documents rules + canonical token list + bypass
    - CLAUDE.md 'Hard rules' section links to the new doc
  outcome_id: MISSION-010

- id: INFRA-1591
  domain: INFRA
  title: "CREDIBLE: PWA visual snapshot tests at 3 breakpoints — Playwright baselines for NOW/AMBIENT/LIBRARY/CONFIG + first-run wizard + cockpit + audit at 375/768/1440px, CI fails on >0.5% pixel delta"
  status: open
  priority: P1
  effort: m
  description: |
    The PWA shell cleanup arc (INFRA-1585 onboarding consolidation, INFRA-1586 header dedup, INFRA-1587 CSS evacuation) is dangerous without a visual regression net. The CSS evacuation alone moves 2,300 lines of styles across ~20 components; manual visual verification doesn't scale and won't catch every pixel.
    
    This gap establishes the safety net. It is also an independent CREDIBLE win — visual regression in CI catches accidental drift that no human will notice in code review.
    
    Stack choice: Playwright (already used for e2e tests in this repo per e2e/ + e2e-tauri/ directories). Playwright's toHaveScreenshot() API is the standard pattern.
    
    Rough shape:
    (a) e2e/pwa-visual/ directory with spec files per surface:
        - cadence-now.spec.ts        — cockpit + sub-tabs
        - cadence-ambient.spec.ts    — live event tail + fleet roster
        - cadence-library.spec.ts    — gaps + sessions + audit + roadmap
        - cadence-config.spec.ts     — providers + tool policy + air-gap + budget
        - first-run-wizard.spec.ts   — visit /v2/?welcome=force, capture chump-first-run-wizard
        - audit-view.spec.ts         — chump-view-audit (PRODUCT-111)
        - error-states.spec.ts       — offline banner, doctor banner, auth toast
    (b) Each spec captures screenshots at 3 viewports: 375x812 (iPhone), 768x1024 (iPad), 1440x900 (laptop).
    (c) Mock backend: e2e/pwa-visual/fixtures/ holds JSON fixtures for /api/dashboard, /api/gap-queue, /api/fleet-status, /api/telemetry/cost, /api/mission-grade, /api/tool-approval-audit, /api/cos/decisions, etc. Playwright route() intercepts requests and serves fixtures — tests run without a live chump --web daemon.
    (d) Snapshot baselines committed under e2e/pwa-visual/__screenshots__/ (organized per spec, per browser, per viewport).
    (e) CI job .github/workflows/pwa-visual.yml runs on PR for any web/v2/** change, fails if any snapshot diff exceeds 0.5% pixel delta (toHaveScreenshot maxDiffPixelRatio: 0.005).
    (f) Operator re-baseline workflow documented in web/v2/README.md (or new docs/process/PWA_VISUAL_TESTING.md):
        - Local: npx playwright test e2e/pwa-visual --update-snapshots
        - Then visually inspect each updated screenshot before committing
    (g) Smoke test scripts/ci/test-pwa-visual-bootstrap.sh — verifies playwright config + fixture loader work; runs ONE spec end-to-end to catch CI breakage before the full suite runs.
    (h) Documentation in PR template: 'Touched web/v2/**? Did you run the visual snapshot suite and review any diffs?'
    
    Theme coverage v1: dark theme only (default). Light + high-contrast added in a follow-up sub-gap if scope creep is a concern (don't block this gap on 3x the screenshot count).
    
    Browser coverage v1: chromium only (cross-browser is a separate concern; this is regression detection not browser-compat).
    
    When picked, run chump gap decompose <ID>; sub-gaps materialize against current view inventory (which may have shifted as PRODUCT-127–131 cockpit-fix gaps land).
  acceptance_criteria:
    - e2e/pwa-visual/ directory with one spec per cadence + first-run + cockpit + audit + error-states
    - Each spec captures at 375/768/1440px viewports
    - Mock backend via Playwright route() — tests run without chump --web daemon
    - Snapshot baselines committed under e2e/pwa-visual/__screenshots__/
    - .github/workflows/pwa-visual.yml runs on PRs touching web/v2/**
    - CI fails if any snapshot diff > 0.5% pixel delta
    - docs/process/PWA_VISUAL_TESTING.md or web/v2/README.md describes operator re-baseline workflow
    - scripts/ci/test-pwa-visual-bootstrap.sh smoke-tests config + one spec end-to-end
    - "PR template note added: 'Touched web/v2/**? Visual snapshots reviewed?'"
    - "Theme + browser coverage: dark + chromium only for v1; follow-up gap filed for light/HC/cross-browser if needed"
  outcome_id: MISSION-010

- id: INFRA-1592
