- id: INFRA-1609
  domain: INFRA
  title: "RESILIENT: self-hosted runner-offline detection + ambient alert — poll gh actions/runners every 2min, emit kind=runner_offline / runner_recovered on status delta; surface in fleet brief + chump fleet doctor; also alert on ci_check_wait > 20min"
  status: done
  priority: P1
  effort: s
  description: |
    Today (2026-05-16) the fleet's audit wait times ballooned from sub-10-min normal to 50-67 min. Root cause: 1 of 4 self-hosted runners (jeffs-macbook-air-10) silently went offline. Nobody noticed for hours. The operator had to manually 'gh api repos/.../actions/runners' to discover it, and I (the head-designer agent) initially misdiagnosed the symptom as 'INFRA-1566 saturation' because the runner-status data wasn't surfaced anywhere.
    
    This is a pure stitching-layer gap: the system has the signal (gh API returns runner status), the fleet has the observation infrastructure (ambient.jsonl + session-start brief + chump fleet doctor), but the wiring between them doesn't exist. Operator visibility into infrastructure health is RESILIENT pillar — broken-runner-not-detected is the same shape as silent-agent-not-detected (which the fleet already alerts on).
    
    Composes with:
    - INFRA-1566 (move runners off Air) — that's the capacity layer; this is the observability layer; both needed
    - INFRA-1603 (PWA hot-reload SSE pipeline) — runner-offline ambient events should surface as PWA toasts via the same channel once INFRA-1603 ships
    - Existing session-start fleet brief — adds a 'Runners: 3/4 online' line with red flag when N<M
    - chump fleet doctor — runner-health becomes a doctor check
    
    Rough shape (Rust-first per META-064 since this writes to ambient.jsonl, persistent daemon, will outlive 3 months):
    
    (a) New Rust binary in crates/chump-runner-watcher (or fold into existing chump-coord crate). Polls 'gh api repos/:owner/:repo/actions/runners' every CHUMP_RUNNER_POLL_INTERVAL_S (default 120s, range 60-600). Uses GH_TOKEN/keyring per existing chump_gh helper.
    (b) Maintains state file .chump/runner-state.json with: {runners: [{name, labels[], status, last_online_at, last_offline_at, baseline}], expected_count, updated_at}. Baseline = max runners ever seen online in the last 7 days (auto-learned, no config needed).
    (c) On status delta detection:
        - new offline: emit kind=runner_offline {name, labels, last_online_at, downtime_s_so_far=0}
        - was offline, now online: emit kind=runner_recovered {name, downtime_s, last_offline_at}
        - count drops below baseline for >5min: emit kind=runner_capacity_degraded {online_count, baseline_count, degraded_for_s, expected_capacity_pct}
    (d) Bonus symptom alert: poll 'gh pr list' periodically; for each open PR with a required check in QUEUED state, if startedAt - createdAt > CHUMP_CI_WAIT_THRESHOLD_S (default 1200s = 20min), emit kind=ci_check_wait_high {pr_number, check_name, wait_s, queued_runs_count}. This catches the SYMPTOM (queue depth) regardless of cause (runner offline, GraphQL throttle, runner crashed mid-job).
    (e) Wire into session-start brief: scripts/dispatch/fleet-status.sh (or wherever the SessionStart hook brief is generated) reads .chump/runner-state.json and prints a 'Runners: N/M online' line; red flag when N<M; show offline runner names.
    (f) Wire into 'chump fleet doctor': new check returns non-zero when runner count < baseline OR any runner offline >5min.
    (g) Wire into 'chump fleet doctor --heal' (INFRA-1595): if INFRA-1595 lands, suggest the heal action ('runner X offline since T — try: launchctl kickstart -k system/com.github.actions-runner.X').
    (h) launchd plist OR systemd timer to keep the watcher running: launchd/chump-runner-watcher.plist following existing pattern (see launchd/ directory).
    (i) Smoke test scripts/ci/test-runner-watcher.sh: fixture gh-api response with 4 runners online → poll → assert no event; mutate fixture to 3 online + 1 offline → second poll → assert kind=runner_offline emitted with correct fields.
    (j) docs/process/RUNNER_HEALTH_MONITORING.md: how it works, how to tune thresholds, recovery playbook ('runner offline → check launchctl status → check disk space → restart actions-runner service').
    
    When picked, run chump gap decompose <ID>; sub-gaps decompose into watcher daemon + ambient events + brief integration + doctor check + tests.
    
    Anti-scope: this gap does NOT auto-restart offline runners (operator action). That's a follow-up if the pattern proves common.
  acceptance_criteria:
    - crates/chump-runner-watcher (or chump-coord) polls gh actions/runners every 60-600s (default 120s, env CHUMP_RUNNER_POLL_INTERVAL_S)
    - .chump/runner-state.json tracks per-runner status + last_online_at + last_offline_at + auto-learned baseline from 7d history
    - Emit kind=runner_offline ambient event on new offline detection with {name, labels, last_online_at}
    - Emit kind=runner_recovered ambient event on recovery with {name, downtime_s}
    - Emit kind=runner_capacity_degraded when online_count < baseline_count for >5min
    - "Bonus: emit kind=ci_check_wait_high {pr_number, check_name, wait_s} when required check QUEUED >CHUMP_CI_WAIT_THRESHOLD_S (default 1200s)"
    - "Session-start fleet brief shows 'Runners: N/M online' line with red flag when N<M; lists offline runner names"
    - chump fleet doctor includes runner-health check; non-zero exit when runner count < baseline OR any offline >5min
    - launchd plist at launchd/chump-runner-watcher.plist keeps watcher running across reboots
    - "scripts/ci/test-runner-watcher.sh: fixture gh-api response, mutation, asserts correct ambient event emitted"
    - docs/process/RUNNER_HEALTH_MONITORING.md documents thresholds + recovery playbook
    - Composes with INFRA-1603 hot-reload SSE so PWA gets runner-offline toast (when INFRA-1603 ships); not a strict dep
  closed_date: '2026-05-24'
  closed_pr: 2273
  outcome_id: MISSION-010

