- id: INFRA-1614
  domain: INFRA
  title: "EFFECTIVE: wire pr_chip_tagged.skills_invoked field + cos digest per-skill yield aggregation — closes the agent learning loop (skill reliability x Mission Yield chip = curriculum bias signal)"
  status: open
  priority: P1
  effort: m
  description: |
    The Mission Yield framework (MISSION_YIELD.md) records per-PR chip-tags (marcus|fleet-quality|dev-tool|noise). The skill system (src/skill_db.rs) records per-skill outcomes (success|failure). These two signals are currently UNCONNECTED — the system knows what skills agents used AND what value each PR produced, but never correlates the two. Without correlation, skill curriculum cannot bias toward marcus-producing techniques and against noise-producing techniques. This is the load-bearing wire that makes the brain self-improving rather than just self-tracking.
  acceptance_criteria:
    - "kind=pr_chip_tagged event gets a new skills_invoked: [] field listing the skill names that were applied during the agent session(s) producing this PR; populated by aggregating skill_manage(action=view) + record_outcome events with the same session_id over the PR lifetime"
    - "src/skill_db.rs gains skill_chip_correlation(name) returning {chips: {marcus, fleet_quality, dev_tool, noise}, yield_weight}"
    - chump cos digest --week computes per-skill yield_weight = (marcus + fleet_quality + dev_tool - reverts_7d) / attempts; surfaces in JSON output
    - chump skill health --json includes chip distribution per skill (additive to INFRA-1613 surface)
    - "scripts/ci/test-skill-chip-correlation.sh: seed synthetic skill outcomes + chip-tags, assert yield_weight computes correctly"
    - docs/strategy/MISSION_YIELD.md gains a Skill correlation section explaining how skill yield feeds the chip distribution
    - EVENT_REGISTRY.yaml updated for the new pr_chip_tagged.skills_invoked field
  notes: |
    wave: 0b (closes the agent learning loop; the load-bearing curriculum-bias connector); chip-prediction: fleet-quality
  outcome_id: MISSION-010

