- id: INFRA-1990
  domain: INFRA
  title: "RESILIENT: hook stdin-drain audit CI gate — count while-read-local_sha loops in scripts/git-hooks/*; fail CI if any hook has >1 such loop without _HOOK_STDIN cache pattern"
  status: done
  priority: P1
  effort: xs
  description: |
    See docs/strategy/THE_FLOOR.md §3 (silent-failure tax sibling).
    Specific prevention for the pattern that caused INFRA-1986 (the
    3-day pre-push silent regression). Source-contract CI gate; no
    runtime instrumentation.
    
    Rough shape: ~30 LOC of bash that greps + counts + checks for
    cache pattern. Single file in scripts/ci/. Bypass env + trailer.
    
    Cheapest possible prevention for a specific known wedge class.
    XS effort.
    
    Will catch: any future commit that adds a stdin-consuming loop
    to a git hook without using the cache pattern. Won't catch:
    other stdin-drain patterns outside git hooks (those are
    INFRA-1996's broader silent-failure-tax scope).
  acceptance_criteria:
    - "New CI gate scripts/ci/test-hook-stdin-drain.sh: greps scripts/git-hooks/* for 'while.*read.*local_sha\\|while.*read.*remote_sha' loops"
    - If any single hook has >1 such loop AND does NOT contain '_HOOK_STDIN' (the cache pattern from INFRA-1986 fix), the gate FAILS with diagnostic naming the offending hook + line numbers
    - "Acceptable patterns: (a) one loop that consumes stdin directly, or (b) multiple loops that all read from a cached '_HOOK_STDIN=$(cat || true)' variable via 'done <<<\"$_HOOK_STDIN\"'"
    - "Bypass: CHUMP_HOOK_STDIN_GATE_BYPASS=1 + commit body trailer 'Hook-Stdin-Gate-Bypass: <reason>' — same pattern as preflight/silent-failure-tax bypasses"
    - "Doc update: docs/process/CLAUDE_GOTCHAS.md gets 'Hook stdin double-drain' entry referencing INFRA-1986 + the canonical _HOOK_STDIN cache pattern"
    - "Validation: gate run against current main passes (post-INFRA-1986 the only hook with >1 loop already uses _HOOK_STDIN)"
    - "Smoke test scripts/ci/test-hook-stdin-drain-fixture.sh: synthetic hook with 2 stdin-consuming loops without cache → assert gate fails; same hook with cache → assert gate passes"
  closed_date: '2026-05-25'
  closed_pr: 2592
  outcome_id: MISSION-010

- id: INFRA-1991
  domain: INFRA
  title: "RESILIENT: cluster auto-rollback — if ci_failure_cluster fires AND blame-bot identifies single suspect commit AND >30min elapsed without fix PR, post 'auto-revert proposed' to ambient with one-click revert link"
  status: open
  priority: P2
  effort: m
  description: |
    See docs/strategy/THE_FLOOR.md (referenced in Phase 3 work). Last
    step in the cluster-RCA → blame → propose-revert pipeline. P2
    because it sits at the end of the chain — needs both detector and
    blame-bot before it can usefully fire.
    
    Rough shape: (a) consumer of regression_attributed events; (b)
    30min sleep timer (launchd plist or simple at(1)/sleep); (c)
    check if cluster still active when timer fires; (d) post comment
    + emit ambient; (e) cancellation listener.
    
    KEY DESIGN: PROPOSE, don't EXECUTE. Auto-revert that fires
    autonomously is too dangerous — a flaky CI run could trigger a
    revert of a good commit. The proposal goes through the recovery
    queue (INFRA-1993) which has the rate limit + audit + auth model.
    
    Sequencing: depends on INFRA-1987 (cluster events), INFRA-1989
    (attribution events), INFRA-1993 (recovery queue executes the
    eventual revert).
  acceptance_criteria:
    - Triggered by kind=regression_attributed events (from INFRA-1989) where blame-bot has identified exactly 1 suspect commit
    - Waits 30min after attribution before proposing rollback (gives the original author time to push a fix)
    - "If after 30min no follow-up PR addresses the suspect commit, emit kind=auto_revert_proposed with: suspect_commit_sha, suspect_pr_number, revert_command (literal 'gh pr revert <N>' or equivalent), cluster_gap_id"
    - Posts comment on the cluster RCA gap with the one-click revert link/command — operator (or recovery queue from INFRA-1993) executes
    - Does NOT execute the revert directly; auto-revert is one approval step away, never autonomous (this is a safety property — auto-mutate via revert is high-risk)
    - "Cancellation: if cluster_id resolves before the 30min timer expires (kind=ci_failure_cluster_resolved), cancel the rollback proposal + emit kind=auto_revert_cancelled"
    - "Smoke test scripts/ci/test-cluster-auto-rollback.sh: synthetic cluster + attribution events, fast-forward time → assert auto_revert_proposed fires; then inject cluster_resolved → assert cancellation"
    - "Audit: every proposal writes one entry to .chump-locks/auto-revert-proposals.log with full context (suspect commit, PRs affected, decision)"
  depends_on: [INFRA-1987, INFRA-1989, INFRA-1993]
  outcome_id: MISSION-010

- id: INFRA-1992
  domain: INFRA
  title: "RESILIENT: floor-temperature signal — chump health --temp returns COLD/WARM/HOT based on silent regressions/trunk-REDs/admin-merges in trailing window; agents read it before claim"
  status: done
  priority: P1
  effort: s
  description: |
    See docs/strategy/THE_FLOOR.md §1 for full rationale. THIS IS THE
    HIGHEST-LEVERAGE PHASE 1 ITEM — smallest unit-change, largest
    behavior-change. Every agent prompt becomes adaptive without any
    other code change.
    
    Rough shape: (a) Rust function in src/health.rs reading ambient.jsonl
    with 24h window, counting the 3 event kinds, returning enum; (b) CLI
    surface in src/main.rs `chump health --temp [--json]`; (c) shell
    wrapper sources env var into agent dispatcher; (d) prompt template
    injection.
    
    Source of truth: ambient.jsonl. Reuses existing wedge-watch +
    cluster detector events. NO new state to manage.
    
    Pairs tightly with INFRA-1987 (cluster detector) — that gap emits
    the kind=ci_failure_cluster event this gap counts.
  acceptance_criteria:
    - "chump health --temp prints one of: COLD | WARM | HOT, plus JSON via --json with the score components"
    - "Scoring: count in trailing 24h (silent-regression events kind=hook_silent_passthrough + cluster events kind=ci_failure_cluster + ambient kind=admin_merge_executed) — COLD if 0, WARM if 1-2, HOT if 3+"
    - New ambient event kind=floor_temp emitted by `chump health --temp` invocations (so we can observe the signal itself; reserved in event-registry-reserved.txt pending formal EVENT_REGISTRY.yaml entry)
    - scripts/dispatch/worker.sh prelude calls chump health --temp and exports CHUMP_FLOOR_TEMP env var; subagent prompt template (prompts/system.md or equivalent) injects the value
    - "Behavior contract: HOT → agents prefer xs+docs gaps; WARM → agents prefer non-env-mutating work + double-verify; COLD → ship aggressively (current behavior)"
    - Smoke test scripts/ci/test-floor-temp.sh — synthetic ambient.jsonl with N=0/2/5 fixture events; assert COLD/WARM/HOT output respectively
    - "Doc update: docs/process/CLAUDE_GOTCHAS.md gets a 'Floor temperature' section explaining the signal"
  closed_date: '2026-05-25'
  closed_pr: 2588
  outcome_id: MISSION-010

- id: INFRA-1993
  domain: INFRA
  title: "RESILIENT: operator-recovery queue — worker agents emit operator_recovery_requested with reason+cluster gap; rate-limited automation services drop-gates+admin-merge+re-arm cycle without Opus on duty"
  status: done
  priority: P1
  effort: l
  description: |
    See docs/strategy/THE_FLOOR.md §5. This gap closes the "Opus on duty"
    bottleneck. Today the admin-merge cycle (drop gates → merge → re-arm)
    requires me + operator's bridge authorization. When neither is
    online, pile-ups stay piled. This converts that human-mediated cycle
    into a queue + service.
    
    Rough shape: (a) new ambient event kind in scripts/dispatch/worker.sh
    (any worker can emit when it detects it's blocked on a cluster);
    (b) new launchd daemon scripts/coord/recovery-queue-service.sh polling
    .chump-locks/ambient.jsonl every 60s; (c) drop+merge+re-arm logic
    cribbed from this PR's commit history (we did it manually 4 times);
    (d) rate limit via simple sliding-window file at
    .chump-locks/recovery-queue-state.json; (e) reuse the ruleset JSON
    backup approach (/tmp/ruleset-backup.json from this session).
    
    SECURITY CONSIDERATION: this daemon has admin-bypass authority. The
    rate limit + audit trail + CHUMP_RECOVERY_QUEUE_PAUSE bypass are the
    discipline. Daemon should refuse to run on a forked PR or a PR not
    owned by the chump bot account.
    
    Depends on INFRA-1987 because the cluster gap ID is the queue's
    primary input — without cluster detection, every PR would request
    individually and the rate limit would shed requests indiscriminately.
  acceptance_criteria:
    - "Worker agents emit kind=operator_recovery_requested ambient event with fields: reason, cluster_gap_id, prs_to_admin_merge (CSV), authorizing_session"
    - "New daemon scripts/coord/recovery-queue-service.sh consumes the queue: rate-limited to max 3 admin-merge cycles per hour fleet-wide, audited"
    - "Recovery cycle: drop required_status_checks rule from ruleset 15133729 (or env-configured) → gh pr merge --squash --admin for each PR in queue → re-arm rule with original contexts (cached at startup)"
    - "Failure-class taxonomy: distinguish (a) recovery succeeded, (b) PR conflicted/already-merged (idempotent), (c) admin permission denied (auth failure), (d) ruleset PUT failed (transient gh API) — each emits distinct ambient kind"
    - "Smoke test scripts/ci/test-recovery-queue.sh: stub gh api, inject 2 queue requests, assert single admin-merge cycle fires + audit ambient event recorded + original gate restored"
    - "Operator override: CHUMP_RECOVERY_QUEUE_PAUSE=1 env disables the daemon (e.g. during planned maintenance); emits kind=recovery_queue_paused"
    - "Audit: every cycle writes one kind=operator_recovery_executed event with full pre/post ruleset diff JSON"
  depends_on: [INFRA-1987]
  closed_date: '2026-05-25'
  closed_pr: 2599
  outcome_id: MISSION-010

- id: INFRA-1994
  domain: INFRA
  title: "RESILIENT: wedge catalog as executable state machine — refactor 13 W-NNN classes from doc-with-playbook to detector_fn+auto_trigger+remediation+escalation; scripts/coord/wedge-watch.sh is starting point (7 detectors)"
  status: done
  priority: P1
  effort: l
  description: |
    See docs/strategy/THE_FLOOR.md §6. Today our wedge catalog is a
    knowledge artifact — humans read it during incidents. It should be
    executable: when the signature fires, the playbook runs.
    
    Rough shape: (a) audit which W-NNN classes have detectors vs only
    docs; (b) for each missing detector, write one (most are <50 LOC of
    grep+gh+jq); (c) for each class with detector but no remediation,
    write the remediation function; (d) state machine wrapper that ties
    detection → remediation → escalation; (e) rate limits to prevent
    remediation oscillation (a remediation that triggers the next
    detection would loop).
    
    KEY DESIGN: remediations that mutate state (admin-merge, push,
    branch protection edits) route through INFRA-1993's recovery queue
    so we get the same rate limit + audit + auth model. Read-only
    remediations (re-arm a daemon, emit a warn, file a gap) can fire
    directly.
    
    Sequencing: ships after INFRA-1993 because the mutation path
    depends on the recovery queue's drop-gates+admin authority.
  acceptance_criteria:
    - Every W-NNN class in docs/process/WEDGE_CLASS_CATALOG.md (currently 13) has a corresponding detector function in scripts/coord/wedge-watch.sh OR a new scripts/coord/wedge-state-machine.sh module
    - "Each detector emits kind=wedge_detected with fields: wedge_class (W-NNN), severity (low/med/high), suspect_paths, recommended_remediation"
    - Each W-NNN class has a remediation function — bash function or callable — that performs the canonical fix from the catalog's playbook section
    - "State machine: detector fires → ambient event → remediation function (rate-limited to once per wedge_class per 30min) → emit kind=wedge_remediated OR kind=wedge_remediation_failed"
    - "Escalation policy: if same wedge_class fires 3x in 24h, emit kind=wedge_chronic and file a META gap for permanent fix"
    - "Companion to recovery queue (INFRA-1993): some remediations require admin-merge — those route through the recovery queue rather than firing directly"
    - "Smoke test scripts/ci/test-wedge-state-machine.sh: inject synthetic wedge_detected for 3 classes, assert remediation fires + audit events recorded + chronic-escalation triggers after 3x"
    - "Migration: existing wedge-watch.sh detectors (7) get remediation wrappers; new detectors added for W-008/W-009/W-010/W-011/W-012/W-013 (6 still doc-only)"
  depends_on: [INFRA-1993]
  closed_date: '2026-05-25'
  closed_pr: 2600
  outcome_id: MISSION-010

- id: INFRA-1995
  domain: INFRA
  title: "EFFECTIVE: chump fleet pulse — single command + /api/fleet/pulse endpoint replacing 5-surface (health+status+ambient+gh-pr+tmux) queries; floor-temp + leases + queue + daemons + last 5 wedges/admin-merges/alerts + pillar rates"
  status: done
  priority: P1
  effort: m
  description: |
    See docs/strategy/THE_FLOOR.md §7. Operators cannot manage what
    they cannot see in one frame. Today that takes 5 separate queries
    against 5 surfaces — Opus does this for the operator, but at higher
    agent counts this is operator-blind territory.
    
    Rough shape: (a) Rust function in src/fleet.rs that aggregates all
    data sources (ambient.jsonl + state.db + gh cache + launchctl); (b)
    CLI surface via main.rs `chump fleet pulse`; (c) HTTP endpoint in
    src/web_server.rs reusing same aggregator; (d) PWA panel component
    consuming /api/fleet/pulse.
    
    KEY DESIGN: this is a READ-ONLY aggregator. Zero state mutation.
    Safe to call from any context. Should complete in <500ms (cache
    everything, no live gh API calls beyond the existing webhook
    cache).
    
    Pairs with INFRA-1992 (floor-temp is one section) and INFRA-1987
    (cluster events are one section).
    
    Supersedes EFFECTIVE-026's "PWA cockpit daemon-set health panel"
    — pulse covers daemon-set health among other things.
