- id: INFRA-2124
  domain: INFRA
  title: "RESILIENT P0: OAuth token auto-refresh chain (INFRA-622) silently broken — ~/.chump/oauth-token.json 3+ weeks stale; same class as INFRA-2101 binary refresh + INFRA-2122 Oracle staleness"
  status: done
  priority: P0
  effort: s
  acceptance_criteria:
    - "1. Diagnosis (updated 2026-05-29T03:10Z): per CLAUDE.md INFRA-622 (\"OAUTH tokens are refreshed to ~/.chump/oauth-token.json every 5 min; workers read from there\"), there should be a daemon/cron that re-extracts the keychain token periodically. Observed: ~/.chump/oauth-token.json's `written_at` is \"2026-05-08T03:32:43Z\" — 3 weeks stale. Headless `claude -p` subprocesses return \"Not logged in\" silently, which cascades into Oracle silently failing for days (4+ days of THE_PATH.md staleness), JIT scheduler stale priorities, dispatch_flatline conditions, etc.\n\n2. Root cause exploration done 2026-05-29:\n   - macOS keychain entry exists: `security find-generic-password -s 'Claude Code-credentials' -a $USER -w` returns 1161-byte JSON blob with `claudeAiOauth.accessToken` (108 chars, `sk-ant-o...` prefix, NOT expired)\n   - Subprocess `claude -p --bare` from a child shell of Claude Code (or launchd) cannot read keychain (macOS access control: login keychain requires GUI session context)\n   - Setting `CLAUDE_CODE_OAUTH_TOKEN=<accessToken>` env: STILL \"Not logged in\"\n   - Setting `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=<accessToken>`: \"Invalid API key\" (OAuth token format ≠ API key format `sk-ant-api03-*`)\n   - Setting `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=<full JSON blob>`: \"Invalid API key\"\n   - Investigation gap: which env var DOES headless `claude -p` consume? `claude -h` docs need re-read; may require a `--token` flag, a custom credential file path, or `ANTHROPIC_AUTH_TOKEN`-style variable not yet identified.\n\n3. Fix path A (deterministic, works today): operator creates a real ANTHROPIC_API_KEY at console.anthropic.com → exports in shell profile (~/.zshenv) + adds to launchd plist EnvironmentVariables for each daemon that spawns `claude -p`. The API-key path is what `claude -p` accepts cleanly.\n\n4. Fix path B (durable, ~m effort): ship the chump OAuth-refresh daemon CLAUDE.md promised:\n   - launchd cron every 5 min runs `scripts/coord/oauth-refresh.sh`\n   - Script: `security find-generic-password -s 'Claude Code-credentials' -a $USER -w "
    - " python3 -c 'json.load... extract accessToken' > ~/.chump/oauth-token.json` (write timestamp included)\n   - All `claude -p` callers (oracle-refresh.sh, dispatch workers, JIT) wrapped to source the token before invocation\n   - Also requires figuring out which env var claude -p actually consumes (see investigation gap in AC#2)\n\n5. Pre-flight guard for downstream consumers: test that `claude -p` works at all before the bounded burst. Emit `oauth_token_stale` if subprocess `claude -p` returns \"Not logged in\" — operator sees in SessionStart digest Alerts(30m). Same pattern as dispatch-flatline-detector (INFRA-2101).\n\n6. After fix: ~/.chump/oauth-token.json's `written_at` advances at least every 30 min (5min cadence × 6× tolerance); zero new `oauth_token_stale` events emitted; oracle-refresh.sh and dispatch chain stop hitting \"Not logged in\".\n\n7. Pairs with: INFRA-2101 (binary refresh silent staleness — same class), INFRA-2122 (Oracle silent failure — downstream symptom), dispatch-flatline-detector pattern, CLAUDE.md INFRA-622 auth modes documentation.\n\n8. Pre-existing test infrastructure exists: scripts/ci/test-oauth-token-refresh.sh, scripts/ci/test-multi-auth.sh. The TESTS exist but the actual refresh daemon does not. Likely INFRA-622 only shipped the documented contract + tests, not the production cron."
  closed_date: '2026-05-29'
  closed_pr: 2714
  outcome_id: MISSION-010

- id: INFRA-2125
  domain: INFRA
  title: "RESILIENT P0: cargo-target-reaper missed 8GB across worktrees — never runs (RunAtLoad=false, daily cron) + only knows ./target/ (misses .cargo-test-target, /tmp/chump-coord-linux-build*, /tmp/chump-cross-build-*)"
  status: done
  priority: P0
  effort: s
  acceptance_criteria:
    - "- Discovered during META-123 parallel-dispatch session 2026-05-28: disk crossed 98% (9.7 GB free) with 8 sub-agents building in parallel. Manual reap recovered 16.5 GB across 3 classes the daemon missed:\n\n  Class A (3.2 GB): /tmp/chump-coord-linux-build, /tmp/chump-coord-linux-build2, /tmp/chump-cross-build-* — Linux cross-build artifacts from scripts/dev/cross-build-linux.sh. Reaper has no rule for these.\n\n  Class B (7.0 GB): /tmp/chump-infra-2116/.cargo-test-target — Sonnet's custom CARGO_TARGET_DIR for test runs. Reaper only scans ./target/, not hidden cargo-target-aliased dirs.\n\n  Class C (6.3 GB): cargo target/ dirs in worktrees with shipped + auto-merge-armed PRs. Reaper sees the active lease and skips, but lease policy should consider \"PR-open and committed\" as a separate gate.\n\n- Reaper has NEVER successfully run on this machine: `launchctl print gui/$UID/dev.chump.cargo-target-reaper` shows `state = not running, last exit code = (never exited)`. Plist has `RunAtLoad = false` + `StartCalendarInterval` (daily) — never triggered between install and disk crisis. This is the same INFRA-1977-class issue (StartInterval-missing-plist) we hit earlier with other launchd daemons.\n\n- Fix in three parts:\n  1. **Make reaper actually run.** Add `RunAtLoad=true` AND change `StartCalendarInterval` to `StartInterval` (3600s hourly). Verify with `launchctl kickstart -k gui/$UID/dev.chump.cargo-target-reaper` then check `last exit code` becomes a number.\n  2. **Expand reaper scope** to catch the three classes above. Pattern-match on these globs: `/tmp/chump-*/.cargo-test-target/`, `/tmp/chump-*/target/`, `/tmp/chump-coord-linux-build*`, `/tmp/chump-cross-build-*`. Reap if older than 1 hour AND not protected by lease policy.\n  3. **Tighten lease-skip policy.** Currently the reaper skips any worktree with an active lease. Should add: \"Reap target/ in lease-active worktree IF the PR is open AND auto-merge armed AND last commit is on origin.\" Reasoning: at that point the work has been pushed; rebuilding cargo target from scratch is bounded recovery cost.\n\n- Verify: install patched daemon, kickstart, confirm `last exit code = 0` and at least one reap event appears in `~/.chump/disk-reaper.log` or `ambient.jsonl`. Crank disk to 90% via dd to test trigger threshold."
  closed_date: '2026-05-29'
  outcome_id: MISSION-010

- id: INFRA-2126
  domain: INFRA
  title: "RESILIENT P1: ACP smoke test cache-key collision — 6 concurrent PRs all fight for same cache key, 5/6 fail"
  status: done
  priority: P1
  effort: s
  acceptance_criteria:
    - "- Repro: open ≥6 PRs that all run the ACP smoke test concurrently against the same self-hosted runner pool (Darwin-arm64).\n- Symptom: Job-level FAILURE despite all in-test assertions PASSing. Failure manifests in the cache-save phase: \"Failed to save: Unable to reserve cache with key v0-rust-acp-smoke-Darwin-arm64-<hash>, another job may be creating this cache.\"\n- Discovered: META-123 Wave 2 dispatch session 2026-05-28. 5 of 6 in-flight PRs (#2705, 2706, 2707, 2708, and #2698 from a different cluster) failed the ACP gate with this exact cache-collision pattern. Manual sequential rerun unblocked all of them.\n- Root cause: rust-cache action key includes the lock-file hash but NOT a per-PR uniqueness suffix, so concurrent runs of the same workflow on the same Cargo.lock all target the same cache slot, and only the first save wins.\n- Fix options:\n  (a) Add `key-suffix: ${{ github.event.pull_request.number }}` (or `github.run_id`) to the rust-cache config in `.github/workflows/acp-smoke.yml` so each PR gets its own cache slot. Tradeoff: slightly less hit rate across PRs.\n  (b) Set `save-if: ${{ github.ref == 'refs/heads/main' }}` so PR runs only RESTORE from cache, never SAVE. Main is the only writer. Tradeoff: cold cache for crates that haven't merged yet.\n  (c) Both — best of both worlds.\n- Verify: open 6 PRs that all run ACP smoke concurrently; all 6 jobs complete without the cache-save error.\n- Cross-references: DOC-063 (CI bottleneck review, just merged) — this is Lever ? in the catalog. Also same class as INFRA-2125 (substrate-noise patterns) and INFRA-755 (observability budget) — the CI infrastructure layer is increasingly the bottleneck, not the code."
  closed_date: '2026-05-29'
  outcome_id: MISSION-010

