- id: INFRA-924
  domain: INFRA
  title: "ZERO-WASTE: fix DECOMP_CODEMOD double-echo producing '0\\n0' arithmetic error in bot-merge.sh"
  status: done
  priority: P1
  effort: xs
  description: |
    grep -c exits 1 when there are zero matches but still writes "0" to stdout.
    The || echo 0 fallback added a second "0", producing "0\n0" in the command
    substitution. Arithmetic on "0\n0" throws a bash syntax error.
    Fix: || echo 0 -> || true (grep already wrote "0"; true suppresses exit-1).
  acceptance_criteria:
    - In scripts/coord/bot-merge.sh line ~1178, replace `|| echo 0` with `|| true` on the DECOMP_CODEMOD grep-c assignment so the command substitution never captures two lines
    - After the fix, running bot-merge.sh with --skip-tests on a branch where all changed files are in docs/gaps/ (100% codemod) produces no arithmetic error and DECOMP_CODEMOD_RATIO=100
    - Running bot-merge.sh with --skip-tests on a branch with zero codemod files produces DECOMP_CODEMOD=0 and no error
    - "No stderr output matching '0\\n0: syntax error in expression' appears on any bot-merge.sh run"
  opened_date: '2026-05-14'
  closed_pr: 1870
  outcome_id: MISSION-010

