- id: META-063
  domain: META
  title: "MISSION: productize redundancy prevention — chump audit-redundancy subcommand + pre-add lint + weekly auto-filed gaps"
  status: done
  priority: P1
  effort: l
  description: |
    MOTIVATION
    
    The 2026-05-14 redundancy audit found 8 distinct families of duplication across the codebase (filed as INFRA-1210 ... INFRA-1218). Looking at the AGE of the duplication:
    - Worktree reapers: 7 files added incrementally over ~6 months. Each one was the "smallest reasonable script" at the time. None of them, individually, looked like a duplicate at filing time.
    - gh wrappers: 4 layers, added one per quarter as throttle / criticality / shim concerns each got their own PR.
    - CI tests grepping src/gap_store.rs: 8 tests added one per gap. Today (INFRA-693 extraction) all 8 broke in lockstep.
    
    The pattern: **each shipped gap incrementally adds a new file; the system has no mechanical preference for extending an existing file over creating a new one.** Audits are point-in-time and the rot resumes the next sprint. We need a productized prevention loop.
    
    PROPOSAL — three layers:
    
    ==== Layer 1: \`chump audit-redundancy\` Rust subcommand ====
    
    Catalogs scripts in scripts/coord/, scripts/ops/, scripts/dispatch/, scripts/dev/, scripts/ci/. For each pair, computes:
    - Function-name overlap (regex \`^[a-z_]+\\(\\)\` extraction + intersection)
    - Top-of-function content similarity (Levenshtein or n-gram on first 20 lines per function)
    - Shared external commands (gh / jq / flock / grep counts)
    - Imported library overlap (\`source \"scripts/lib/X.sh\"\`)
    - Hardcoded path collisions (e.g. multiple scripts referencing scripts/coord/gap-claim.sh)
    
    Output: JSON report with per-pair similarity score + recommended consolidation target.
    Subcommands:
      chump audit-redundancy            — print pairs above threshold (default 0.6)
      chump audit-redundancy --json     — machine-readable
      chump audit-redundancy --file-gaps — auto-file P2 gaps for each cluster (with dedup against existing INFRA-12xx)
      chump audit-redundancy --against <new-file>  — pre-add lint mode
    
    ==== Layer 2: Pre-add lint (CI gate) ====
    
    When a PR adds a new file in scripts/coord/, scripts/ops/, scripts/dispatch/, or scripts/ci/, fast-checks runs:
      chump audit-redundancy --against <new-file>
    If similarity > 0.7 to an existing file, fail with a directive: "extend <existing-file> or justify in commit body with 'Redundancy-OK: <reason>'."
    
    This is the forcing function. The fleet can't ship a 5th reaper without an explicit override.
    
    ==== Layer 3: Weekly auto-audit via launchd ====
    
    dev.chump.audit-redundancy.plist runs weekly:
      chump audit-redundancy --file-gaps --since-last-run
    File any new clusters as gaps tagged 'auto-redundancy-audit'. Curator agent picks them up next pillar cycle.
    
    ACCEPTANCE
    
    1. \`chump audit-redundancy\` Rust subcommand in src/audit_redundancy.rs; works against scripts/coord/, scripts/ops/, scripts/dispatch/, scripts/dev/, scripts/ci/.
    2. CI gate in fast-checks: any PR adding a script in those dirs runs --against mode; fails on similarity > 0.7 unless commit body has 'Redundancy-OK:' trailer.
    3. launchd plist installer + script for the weekly run.
    4. The 2026-05-14 audit findings (INFRA-1210..1218) are detected by --json mode at the same cluster boundaries (regression test).
    5. Operator playbook in docs/process/REDUNDANCY_PREVENTION.md: how to read the report, how to use --against pre-flight, how the override works.
    
    OUT OF SCOPE
    
    - Cross-language redundancy detection (Rust vs Shell vs Python) — start with shell-only; add Rust if effective.
    - Auto-refactoring. The tool reports + files gaps; humans/Opus pick the consolidation target.
    
    WHY P1
    
