         zero false-positive failures, full local-vs-CI parity
      2. A2A world-class — agent-to-agent coordination spine matures
         from emergent (INFRA-1115 broadcast/inbox) to first-class
         delivery + routing layer
      3. Owner-by-scope — agents claim by role/skill/concern, NOT by
         file path; file-leases retire in favour of conflict-resolver
         budgeting (INFRA-1488 already shipped)
    
    Why now: tonight's session surfaced N²/F lease-collision math at
    6 workers. Three of my 90-minute work blocks were stopped cold by
    lease overlaps on append-only metadata files (event-registry-
    reserved.txt, chump-commit.sh) and broad-scoped META-071 leases
    (docs/gaps, scripts/ci). At the roadmap's 50-worker target, the
    file-lease model is mathematically dead. The emergent
    curator-opus-target / -ci-audit / -handoff role split from today's
    sprint IS the answer pattern; this gap formalises it.
    
    Decomposition (3 child gaps):
      - INFRA-1861 — CI/QA 100% (child A)
      - INFRA-1862 — A2A world-class (child B)
      - INFRA-1863 — Owner-by-scope claims (child C)
    
    Vision doc: docs/strategy/ROLE_SCOPED_FLEET_2026-05-23.md
  acceptance_criteria:
    - "docs/strategy/ROLE_SCOPED_FLEET_2026-05-23.md ships in PR #1: names the 3 children, defines the migration order, gives the 6-week timeline, captures operator's 3-priority statement verbatim"
    - Three child gaps (INFRA-1861/1862/1863) filed with real AC (not TODO boilerplate); each has its own ship plan + owning curator role
    - "Migration order documented and respected: CI/QA hardening (child A) → A2A spine (child B) → owner-by-scope (child C). Reason: child C depends on the conflict-resolver running reliably, which needs CI/QA at 100% AND A2A spine in place to coordinate the conflict-resolver outputs"
