- id: META-124
  domain: META
  title: "[UMBRELLA] Integration-cycle ship pipeline — batched-default fleet ship with 4 operating modes + bisect-on-red + audit preservation (Bet-1 + DOC-063 Lever 1+3)"
  status: done
  priority: P1
  effort: xl
  acceptance_criteria:
    - "UMBRELLA per docs/strategy/INTEGRATION_CYCLE_2026-05-29.md (draft at /tmp/INTEGRATION_CYCLE_2026-05-29.md; will ship to docs/strategy/ as the first child).\n\n## Problem statement\n\nPer-PR ship discipline costs us 30-40 min P50 latency, cache-key collisions at concurrency > 4, 20+ CI gates × N concurrent PRs ÷ 4 runners floor, multi-times-per-day GraphQL exhaustion, and a 17-daemon operational surface mostly compensating for per-PR friction. Today's session (META-123 dispatch) was the worst case: 9 PRs took 5+ hours to settle, half via flake-rerun. The friend's question landed: we're optimizing for distributed-open-source-contributor problems we don't have. Bet 5 NATS substrate (INFRA-2102) landed last night and is exactly the coordination layer the alternative needs.\n\n## The four operating modes\n\n"
    - " Mode "
    - " Trigger "
    - " Ship as "
    - " Volume "
    - "\n"
    - "---"
    - "---"
    - "---"
    - "---"
    - "\n"
    - " A. Batched (DEFAULT) "
    - " every 30 min OR 5+ gaps queued OR LOC>1500 (whichever first, 5-min time-floor) "
    - " single integration-YYYY-MM-DD-HHMM PR "
    - " 80-90% of fleet work "
    - "\n"
    - " B. Per-PR (REVIEW-REQUIRED) "
    - " title prefix REVIEW: OR external-collab lane OR operator manual flag "
    - " individual PR (as today) "
    - " 10-20% "
    - "\n"
    - " C. Hot-fix (URGENT) "
    - " P0 + title TRUNK-RED/HOTFIX/SECURITY OR chump gap hot-fix "
    - " individual PR, runner-1 priority "
    - " <1% "
    - "\n"
    - " D. External-repo "
    - " external_repo: tag (META-123 flow) "
    - " ships to customer repo, not chump main "
    - " N/A "
    - "\n\n## Lifecycle (Mode A integration cycle)\n\n1. ATOMIC CLAIM via chump-coord (NATS KV slot, 30-min TTL)\n2. CANDIDATE SELECTION: sort work-board by P0-first then queue time; take ≤10 OR ≤LOC budget\n3. INTEGRATION BRANCH: integration-YYYY-MM-DD-HHMM off origin/main; git merge --no-ff each candidate with Batched-Under: trailer\n4. PREFLIGHT: scripts/dev/cross-build-linux.sh + cargo fmt --check + clippy -D warnings + relevant test-*.sh; budget 8 min; reuses chump preflight INFRA-1670\n5. DECISION: green → SHIP; red → BISECT\n6a. SHIP: one PR with manifest body listing N child gaps; gh pr merge --auto --squash; each child gap chump gap ship --integration <id>\n6b. BISECT: git bisect run scripts/dev/integration-bisect-step.sh identifies offender in O(log N) preflight runs; quarantine offender, ship rest; quarantined gap returns to work-board with status=bisect_quarantined\n7. CLEANUP: release integration slot; integration branch kept 24h for audit/replay; cargo-target-reaper (INFRA-2125) handles worktrees\n\n## Children (15 sub-gaps, sequenced)\n\nWAVE 1 (foundation — parallel-safe, blocks Wave 2+3):\n- C1 Strategy doc shipped to docs/strategy/INTEGRATION_CYCLE_2026-05-29.md (Opus self — design call)\n- C2 chump-integrator-daemon core (Phase 1 dry-run mode only; new Rust binary crates/chump-integrator/)\n- C3 install-chump-integrator-launchd.sh + plist + REQUIRED_DAEMONS registration\n- C4 Ambient event kinds (8 new) + EVENT_REGISTRY.yaml + scanner anchors\n\nWAVE 2 (depends on C2, parallel-safe):\n- C5 bot-merge.sh routing changes (recognize mode: batched / REVIEW: / hot-fix prefixes)\n- C6 chump gap show — shipped_in resolution (integration ID, PR, commit, merge SHA)\n- C7 Per-commit Batched-Under trailer enforcement + integration PR body template\n- C8 integration-bisect-step.sh + bisect-on-red logic in C2\n- C9 Quarantine queue + bisect_quarantined gap status + work-board re-enqueue\n- C10 chump-pr-pulse-consumer (post-cycle per-gap branch prune daemon)\n\nWAVE 3 (depends on Wave 1+2, sequential):\n- C11 Phase 2 sampling logic — CHUMP_INTEGRATOR_SAMPLING_PCT knob; 10% live / 90% dry-run\n- C12 Phase 3 default-on docs + flag flip across CLAUDE.md, AGENTS.md, OPERATOR_PLAYBOOK.md\n- C13 External-facing doc updates: PITCH.md, DEMO_5MIN.md, HIDDEN_GEMS.md, ROADMAP_MARCUS.md\n- C14 L2-SLO-6 bisect-quarantine rate metric + chump health --slo-check addition\n- C15 chump kpi report integration-cycle dashboard (latency, CI runs/gap, runner util, bisect rate)\n\n## Phased rollout\n\nPhase 1 (1 session): C1-C4 + C2 in DRY-RUN mode. Daemon walks lifecycle, stops before gh pr create, logs to ~/.chump/integrator-dry-run.log. Operator observes 24h. Calibrate thresholds.\n\nPhase 2 (1-2 weeks): C5-C11 + sampling. CHUMP_INTEGRATOR_SAMPLING_PCT=10. Every 10th eligible batch goes live; rest dry-run. Operator monitors latency + bisect rate. Tune thresholds down until bisect-quarantine <5%.\n\nPhase 3 (after Phase 2 metrics): C12-C13. Default-on. Per-PR mode is opt-in only. Marcus-facing doc updates.\n\nPhase 4 (continuous): C14-C15. Metric-driven tuning. Per-gap-class thresholds.\n\n## Success criteria (Phase 3 targets vs today's baseline)\n\n"
    - " Metric "
    - " Today "
    - " Phase 3 target "
    - " Source "
    - "\n"
    - "---"
    - "---"
    - "---"
    - "---"
    - "\n"
    - " P50 gap-to-main latency "
    - " 30-40 min "
    - " <20 min "
    - " chump kpi report "
    - "\n"
    - " Mean CI runs per shipped gap "
    - " ~1.0 "
    - " ~0.15 "
    - " runner job count "
    - "\n"
    - " Runner peak utilization "
    - " ~80% (pegged) "
    - " <50% "
    - " self-hosted-runner-cache metrics "
    - "\n"
    - " Bisect-quarantine rate "
    - " N/A "
    - " <5% of cycles "
    - " new ambient event "
    - "\n"
    - " GraphQL exhaustion / day "
    - " 2-4 "
    - " <0.5 "
    - " api-cost-leaderboard.sh "
    - "\n"
    - " Operator flake-rerun interventions / day "
    - " 5-10 "
    - " <1 "
    - " manual_rescue in fleet-brief "
    - "\n\n## What this preserves\n\n- GitHub PRs still happen (just as integration cycles, not per-gap). Audit trail strengthens via richer PR bodies + ambient manifest.\n- Mode B per-PR remains available for review-required work; operator's existing keystrokes work.\n- Same machinery serves solo dev + AI fleet + SMB team + enterprise. Mode is a per-gap knob, not a build-time fork.\n- Bet 5 substrate is the foundation, not duplicated.\n\n## Open questions (operator decisions before C2 implementation)\n\n1. Cadence default — 30 min (drafted) vs 60 min vs hourly-on-the-hour?\n2. Max-batch default — 10 (drafted) vs 20? (bisect vs amortization tradeoff)\n3. Hot-fix bypass integrator entirely (drafted) OR high-priority lane within it?\n4. REVIEW: as only Mode B opt-in (operator preference?) OR auto-tag certain gap classes (external-collab, partnership)?\n5. Phase 1 dry-run duration — 24h, 72h, week?\n\n## Cross-references\n\n- DOC-063 (CI bottleneck review) — quantified Lever 1 + Lever 3 land here\n- INFRA-2102 (NATS A2A substrate) — foundation; landed yesterday\n- INFRA-2125 (cargo-target-reaper) — disk hygiene works with new model\n- INFRA-2126 (ACP cache-key collision) — symptom this strategy addresses structurally\n- META-123 (external-repo flow) — Mode D defined there; complementary\n- INFRA-1670 + INFRA-1673 (chump preflight + local CI discipline) — reused at integration step\n\n## Effort\n\n~3 working sessions (~12 hrs) to Phase 1 dry-run live. Most slices ship as parallelizable Sonnet dispatches once decomposed."
  closed_date: '2026-06-05'
  closed_pr: 2772
  outcome_id: MISSION-010

- id: META-125
  domain: META
  title: "[UMBRELLA] Live A2A consensus pipeline — curators-as-NATS-subscribers + chump consensus ask/vote/resolve + auto-roadmap-rerank (seconds not weeks)"
  status: done
  priority: P1
  effort: xl
  acceptance_criteria:
    - "UMBRELLA per docs/strategy/LIVE_A2A_CONSENSUS_2026-05-29.md (to be drafted as child C1).\n\n## Problem statement (operator-named 2026-05-29)\n\nToday's A2A surface fakes liveness. broadcast.sh dual-publishes to NATS + inboxes; the NATS leg is theoretically real-time but NO curator runs a persistent NATS subscriber. They poll inboxes at session-start, which means cross-curator deliberation has a 4-24h latency floor. Decisions that should take seconds (does this strategy pivot the roadmap? do 9 curators concur?) take days, and the meantime is lost productivity. Today's META-124 broadcasts: sent at 13:18, evidence shows zero curator subscribers active, replies blocked on next session-start for each.\n\nThe substrate FOR live consensus exists (INFRA-2102 NATS substrate, INFRA-1803 consensus voting ported from proprietary, chump-coord watch + help-request + work-board). It's not wired into a real-time decision surface.\n\n## Three goals\n\n1. **Curators-as-NATS-subscribers** — each canonical curator-opus-* role runs a persistent subscriber daemon that listens on chump.events.consensus.> (or chump.curator.<role>.>) and triggers the curator's reasoning loop on receipt. Wakes the role in seconds, not days.\n\n2. **chump consensus subcommand** — new CLI: ask/vote/resolve/pivot lifecycle. Operator (or another curator) can fire a strategic question to N curators, set quorum + timeout, get a confidence-weighted aggregate decision back within seconds.\n\n3. **Auto roadmap re-rank** — when consensus pivots a decision, gap-store mutations happen automatically: re-rank priorities, mark superseded work as backlog with rationale, surface new top-of-queue gaps. No manual operator intervention to re-sequence.\n\n## Lifecycle of a chump consensus decision\n\n  1. ASK: chump consensus ask \"<question>\" --quorum 5 --timeout 60s --tag <strategic-tag>\n       - Generates consensus_id (uuid)\n       - Publishes to chump.events.consensus.ask with question + tag + timeout\n       - Emits ambient kind=consensus_ask_started\n\n  2. ROUTE: subscriber daemons receive on their chump.curator.<role>.consensus subject\n       - Each curator's daemon evaluates: does this question fall in my lane? confidence high/med/low?\n       - If yes: triggers per-role reasoning (could be claude -p, MLX local, or pre-trained quick-vote model)\n       - Reasoning produces: {vote: agree/disagree/abstain, confidence: high/med/low, rationale: string}\n\n  3. VOTE: chump consensus vote <consensus-id> --vote agree --confidence high --rationale \"...\"\n       - Publishes to chump.events.consensus.vote.<consensus-id>\n       - Emits ambient kind=consensus_vote_cast\n\n  4. AGGREGATE: chump-consensus-aggregator-daemon waits for quorum OR timeout\n       - At timeout: tallies votes, computes confidence-weighted decision\n       - Emits ambient kind=consensus_resolved with full breakdown\n\n  5. PIVOT (optional): chump consensus roadmap-pivot <consensus-id>\n       - For decisions that re-rank work:\n         - re-prioritize gaps matching the consensus topic tag\n         - mark superseded gaps as backlogged with rationale\n         - surface new top-of-queue\n       - Emits ambient kind=roadmap_rerank_applied\n\n## Children (10 sub-gaps, sequenced)\n\nWAVE 1 (foundation — parallel-safe):\n- C1 Strategy doc docs/strategy/LIVE_A2A_CONSENSUS_2026-05-29.md (Opus self — design call)\n- C2 NATS subject taxonomy: chump.events.consensus.{ask,vote,resolved}.>, chump.curator.<role>.consensus\n- C3 9 new ambient event kinds: consensus_ask_started, consensus_routed_to_curator, consensus_vote_cast, consensus_quorum_reached, consensus_timeout, consensus_resolved, consensus_decision_emitted, roadmap_rerank_proposed, roadmap_rerank_applied\n- C4 chump-curator-subscriber daemon — Rust binary in crates/chump-curator-subscriber; per-role NATS subscriber + per-role reasoning hook; runs as launchd KeepAlive per role\n\nWAVE 2 (depends on C2-C4):\n- C5 chump consensus ask subcommand — publishes question, returns consensus_id, optionally blocks-and-waits for resolve\n- C6 chump consensus vote subcommand — for curators to publish their vote\n- C7 chump consensus resolve / status subcommands — aggregator + queryable state\n- C8 chump-consensus-aggregator-daemon — Rust binary; subscribes to chump.events.consensus.vote.>; computes confidence-weighted decision at quorum-or-timeout; emits decision\n- C9 install-chump-consensus-launchd.sh for the aggregator daemon\n\nWAVE 3 (depends on Wave 1+2):\n- C10 chump consensus roadmap-pivot — applies decision to gap-store priority + backlog; backlog gaps gain rationale field linking to consensus_id; chump session-summary surfaces last-N decisions\n\n## Connection to META-124 (integration cycles)\n\nMETA-124 sets the SHIP rhythm (batched cycles). META-125 sets the DECIDE rhythm (consensus cycles). They compose:\n- Strategic decisions go to consensus (META-125) for curator weigh-in\n- Tactical work goes to integration cycles (META-124) for batched ship\n- Roadmap re-rank from consensus feeds the integration scheduler\n\n## Success criteria\n\n"
    - " Metric "
    - " Today "
    - " Target "
    - " How measured "
    - "\n"
    - "---"
    - "---"
    - "---"
    - "---"
    - "\n"
    - " Consensus question to decision wall time "
    - " 4-24h (next session-start latency) "
    - " <90s (timeout default) "
    - " new ambient timing "
    - "\n"
    - " Quorum hit rate "
    - " N/A "
    - " >80% (5 of 9 curators) "
    - " consensus_quorum_reached count "
    - "\n"
    - " Roadmap re-rank coverage "
    - " 0 (manual) "
    - " >70% of pivoted decisions auto-apply "
    - " roadmap_rerank_applied count "
    - "\n"
    - " Operator hand-trigger reduction "
    - " N/A "
    - " Operator types fewer chump gap set commands per week "
    - " chump kpi report --consensus "
    - "\n\n## Open questions for operator (before C4 implementation)\n\n1. **Curator-subscriber substrate** — Rust binary OR per-role claude -p in tmux? Rust = cleaner, ~weeks; claude -p = today, higher cost but simpler.\n2. **Default quorum** — 5 of 9 curators (drafted) or weighted by lane-relevance?\n3. **Vote confidence weighting** — equal weight per vote OR weight by curator's lane match to question?\n4. **Auto-pivot threshold** — apply re-rank automatically when consensus_resolved has agree>=70%, or always require operator confirmation?\n5. **Backlog gap rationale schema** — JSON field on gap OR separate audit log?\n\n## Cross-references\n\n- META-124 (integration cycles) — DECIDE rhythm + SHIP rhythm compose\n- INFRA-2102 (NATS A2A substrate) — foundation for live subscribers\n- INFRA-1803 (consensus voting from proprietary) — primitive we extend\n- INFRA-1115 (mailboxes) — fallback for offline curators\n- INFRA-2144..2150 (A2A housekeeping bugs) — preconditions; broadcast surface needs polish first\n- META-046 (PM curation role) — operator's lane; consensus complements not replaces"
  closed_date: '2026-06-05'
  closed_pr: 2781
  outcome_id: MISSION-010

- id: META-126
  domain: META
  title: "[CHILD of META-125] event-sourcing for gap mutations — chump gap reserve/update publishes chump.gap.* event; single consumer materializes state.db + YAMLs (single-writer pattern, audit-grade ordering)"
  status: open
  priority: P3
  effort: m
  acceptance_criteria:
    - "CHILD OF META-125 — full event-sourcing pivot for gap mutations. Defer until META-124 + META-125 land (they share the NATS substrate; don't pivot 3 substrates at once).\n\nVision: chump gap reserve / update / ship / close publishes to chump.gap.* subjects. Single consumer (chump-gap-materializer-daemon) reads the stream and writes to state.db + individual docs/gaps/*.yaml. Eliminates concurrent-write races entirely (single-writer pattern). Becomes Kafka-style: ordered, replayable, audit-grade.\n\nChildren to file when picked:\n- C1 Subject taxonomy: chump.gap.reserved, chump.gap.updated, chump.gap.shipped, chump.gap.closed\n- C2 chump-gap-materializer-daemon (Rust, single consumer of chump.gap.>)\n- C3 chump gap reserve/update/ship/close switch from direct state.db write to NATS publish\n- C4 Replay-from-history mode: rebuild state.db from chump.gap.> jetstream replay\n- C5 Audit dashboard: kpi report --gap-mutations shows reserve/update/ship/close rate per day\n- C6 Migration plan: dry-run mode where both paths run side-by-side and reconcile\n\nSuccess criteria:\n- Zero concurrent-write corruptions (today's failure class becomes structurally impossible)\n- Replayable: chump gap restore --from-jetstream rebuilds state.db cleanly\n- Sub-100ms reserve latency under typical fleet load\n\nCross-references INFRA-2102 (substrate), META-125 (consensus pipeline — same NATS bus), META-124 (integration cycles — same substrate), INFRA-2177 (state.db simplification first), INFRA-2178 (KV counter is a partial-credit step toward this)."
  outcome_id: MISSION-010

- id: META-127
  domain: META
  title: "[UMBRELLA] AI Agent Suite for fleet P&E management — productize 9 curator roles + N missing roles + standardize role-doc template + make installable on any repo"
  status: done
  priority: P1
  effort: xl
  acceptance_criteria:
    - "UMBRELLA per operator framing 2026-05-29: the 9-curator consensus pattern we operated today (META-124/125 review in ~5 min each) worked BECAUSE each curator had crystal-clear lane scope. Harvester's META-125-is-a-port finding is the strongest example — would never have surfaced without \"arsenal-look-first\" mandate.\n\nProductize this as a SUITE that any org can install on their repos. Chump = substrate. Suite = the team. Marcus M-B canonical demo becomes: \"here's your AI P&E team, watch them deliberate.\"\n\n## Two-axis productization\n\n### Axis 1: Audit existing 9 curators against quality criteria\n\nFor each: curator-opus-ci-audit, decompose, external-collab, handoff, harvester, infra-watcher, md-links, observability, target. Score on:\n- Lane crispness (one sentence, no overlap, no drift)\n- Output shape (does FEEDBACK come back in lane-specific structure?)\n- Cross-references (does the role know which adjacent lanes hand off to it / it hands off to?)\n- Verification gate (does the role flag when its own work has TODO AC, like target did?)\n- Confidence calibration (handoff lowered to 0.75 after a false-positive — this should be a built-in pattern)\n\nToday's evidence: harvester + ci-audit + infra-watcher + observability + decompose all delivered substantive findings; handoff had a false-positive; external-collab + target had own-lane TODO-AC issues. Roles need a self-audit step + calibration loop.\n\n### Axis 2: File missing roles for full P&E management\n\nEngineering management gaps:\n- C-roadmap-keeper: owns docs/ROADMAP.md priority ranking; updates from consensus + ship signal\n- C-velocity-tracker: P50 ship-time, throughput, flake rate trends; surfaces regressions\n- C-gap-prioritizer: owns picker policy; re-ranks from data\n- C-debt-tracker: technical debt audit; highest-cost-debt surfacing\n- C-architecture-coach: when new gaps arrive, asks \"does this fit our architecture or fork it\"\n- C-dispatch-policy: owns META-069; when Sonnet vs Opus vs claude-code-host\n- C-release-manager: ship cadence, deployment story, blocks not-ready ships\n- C-incident-commander: trunk-red recovery, cross-curator coordination\n- C-security-auditor: periodic security review; CVE tracking\n- C-performance-tracker: latency / throughput regressions\n\nProduct management gaps:\n- C-competitive-intel: monitors Cursor, Cline, Aider, etc.; files match/diff gaps\n- C-customer-journey: tracks specific customers (Marcus, Patrick) through milestone arcs\n- C-pricing-packaging: for enterprise pivot\n- C-strategist: pivot-decision rationale; cross-cuts when consensus diverges\n\nPeople / strategy / governance:\n- C-historian: captures lessons; prevents re-litigation; auto-resurfaces relevant past decisions\n- C-pm-curator: operator-facing audit; META-046 lineage\n\nDecision call per role: ESSENTIAL (v1 suite), NICE-TO-HAVE (v2), DEFER (only if Chump grows that need).\n\n### Children (planned, not yet filed)\n\nC1: 9-curator audit deliverable — score each role on the 5 criteria above; surface \"harvester is the gold standard, others gap\"\nC2: Standardized role-doc template (.claude/agents/<role>.md schema) with required sections: Lane scope, Inbox watcher, 5-step protocol, Discipline rules, Don't section, Cross-references, Self-audit checklist, Confidence calibration loop\nC3: Missing role audit — pick 5-8 of the proposed gaps above; file each with role-doc skeleton; pilot 1-2\nC4: NATS-subscriber daemon for each role (depends on META-125 — when consensus pipeline lands, each role gets a persistent subscriber per its lane subject chump.curator.<role>.*)\nC5: Installable suite — packaging the .claude/agents/ directory + canonical loop scripts + curator inbox setup as a one-command install for any repo\nC6: Repo-agnostic mode — current curators assume Chump-specific paths (state.db, ambient.jsonl). Generalize: per-repo state + ambient configurable\nC7: Suite-level metrics — number of curators active, FEEDBACK rate, consensus convergence rate, time-to-decision\nC8: Marcus demo of the suite — install Chump P&E Suite on derelict; demo curator weigh-in on Patrick's ideas/TODO.md decisions\n\n## Connection to META-124 + META-125 + META-126\n\n- META-125 (consensus pipeline) is the ENABLER — without persistent NATS-subscriber curators, the suite is async-only\n- META-126 (event-sourcing gap mutations) is the audit-grade backing — every curator FEEDBACK leaves an audit trail\n- META-124 (integration cycles) is what the suite SHIPS through — curator-produced gaps go through batched integration\n\n## Success criteria\n\n- Suite installable on a fresh repo in <5 min (single command)\n- 80%+ of operator P&E decisions go through curator consensus, not operator hand-judgment\n- Time from question to consensus decision <5 min (productizes today's 5-min manual pattern)\n- Curator output quality: at least 70% of FEEDBACK produces actionable insight (not \"every option has merit\" hedge)\n- External demo-able: any org can see the suite working on their repo within 1 install + 1 question\n\n## Open questions\n\n1. Suite size — pick 12 essential roles for v1? Or start with the 9 + 3 critical adds (roadmap-keeper, velocity-tracker, historian)?\n2. Self-curation — should one role audit the others? Or external observer?\n3. Confidence calibration — how should false-positives like handoff's INFRA-2167 feed back into role definition / future confidence weighting?\n4. Repo-agnostic vs Chump-specific — full generalization or \"Chump P&E Suite\" stays Chump-flavored as v1?\n5. Pricing — if this productizes as a Marcus-sellable, what's the unit?"
  closed_date: '2026-06-05'
  closed_pr: 2776
  outcome_id: MISSION-010

- id: META-128
  domain: META
  title: "[UMBRELLA] Chump disk-aware fleet — per-node inventory + pre-action disk check + adaptive fleet scaler + multi-node routing (Bet 5 ready)"
  status: done
  priority: P1
  effort: l
  acceptance_criteria:
    - "UMBRELLA per operator framing 2026-05-29: chump should always know what kind of disk space is available to it on its node(s) and plan accordingly when scaling fleets or working alone. Today's evidence the gap is biting us:\n- 98% disk crisis during META-123 cascade; manual reap recovered 16 GB\n- Wave 1 dispatch concern about 6-12 GB burst (infra-watcher curator gated on this)\n- INFRA-2188 (sibling-found): cargo-target-reaper misses ~/.cache/chump-runner — another disk leak class discovered\n- Operator pings about disk repeatedly this session\n- Reaper post-ship trigger (INFRA-2181) ships AFTER the burst happens, not BEFORE\n\nPattern: chump REACTS to disk pressure (operator reap → emergency mode → fleet pause) rather than PLANNING for it.\n\n## The vision\n\nEvery chump action that consumes disk (claim worktree, cargo build, integration cycle, parallel dispatch) consults a disk planner BEFORE proceeding. The planner knows: (a) what's free per node, (b) what this action will cost, (c) what the projected ceiling is. It returns OK / WAIT / REFUSE. The fleet scaler uses the same planner to size fleets adaptively. Multi-node setups (Bet 5) route work to the node with disk headroom.\n\n## Architecture (4 layers)\n\n### Layer 1: Per-node disk inventory\n- New `chump-disk-inventory-daemon` (or extend infra-watcher): polls `df` + `du` for known consumer paths every 30s\n- Publishes to NATS subject `chump.disk.inventory.<node-id>` AND writes `~/.chump/disk-inventory.json` snapshot\n- Tracks: total/free/used, top-N consumers (/tmp/chump-*, ~/.cache/chump-runner, /tmp/chump-coord-linux-build*, etc.), available-headroom = free - reserved\n- Per-node identity from `hostname` + node-id from `~/.chump/node-id.txt`\n\n### Layer 2: Action cost model\n- `docs/process/DISK_COST_MODEL.yaml` — per-action-class disk cost estimate\n- Examples: chump_claim_worktree = 50 MB; cargo_build_debug = 2 GB; cargo_build_release = 800 MB; integration_cycle_N_gaps = N * 1.5 GB; preflight_full = 500 MB; cross_build_linux = 800 MB; sonnet_dispatch_with_worktree = ~2.5 GB\n- Updated by observability curator (lane fit) based on actual measurements over time\n- Reads from a separate `~/.chump/disk-cost-observed.jsonl` rolling log\n\n### Layer 3: Pre-action disk check (`chump disk plan`)\n- New CLI: `chump disk plan <action-class> [--count N] [--node NODE-ID]`\n- Returns: `{ status: OK"
    - WAIT
    - "REFUSE, projection: {free_now_gb, cost_gb, free_after_gb, threshold_gb}, alternative: <suggested-action-if-refuse> }`\n- `chump claim`, `chump fleet up`, integrator daemon (META-124/C2) all call this first\n- Override: `CHUMP_DISK_PLAN_BYPASS=1` with reason emitted as ambient `kind=disk_plan_bypassed`\n- Refuse triggers: free_after_gb < 5 GB (configurable via CHUMP_DISK_FLOOR_GB)\n\n### Layer 4: Adaptive fleet scaler + multi-node routing\n- `chump fleet up N` reads disk inventory + cost model; refuses N if projected disk crash; suggests max-safe-N\n- `chump fleet auto-scale` cron-fires every 5 min; SCALES DOWN when disk < 20 GB free; SCALES UP when > 60 GB free + ship-rate healthy\n- Multi-node (Bet 5): `chump dispatch <gap>` routes to node with most disk headroom (publishes via chump-coord assign daemon FLEET-034 with new chump.work.<priority>.<class>.<node-with-disk-headroom> subject)\n- Per-node disk-pause: if ANY node disk < 5 GB free, that node pauses work (refuses new claims) but others continue\n\n## Children (8 sub-gaps, 4 waves)\n\n### Wave 1 (foundation — parallel-safe)\n- C1 docs/strategy/DISK_AWARE_FLEET_2026-05-29.md (Opus self — design call) — full vision\n- C2 chump-disk-inventory-daemon — new Rust binary crates/chump-disk-inventory; polls df + per-path du; publishes to NATS + writes snapshot\n- C3 install-chump-disk-inventory-launchd.sh + plist — KeepAlive=true long-runner per INFRA-2182 fix\n- C4 docs/process/DISK_COST_MODEL.yaml — seed with measured costs from today's session evidence; observability curator owns updates\n\n### Wave 2 (depends on C2 + C4)\n- C5 chump disk plan + status + budget CLI subcommands — surface the inventory + cost model to operators and other chump subprocesses\n- C6 chump claim integration — call chump disk plan before atomic claim; refuse with helpful message if projected unsafe\n- C7 chump fleet up + auto-scale disk-aware — scaler reads inventory before sizing; auto-scale cron-fires with safety bounds\n\n### Wave 3 (multi-node — depends on Bet 5)\n- C8 NATS routing by disk headroom (chump-coord assign daemon extension) — Bet 5 hardware decision unblocks\n\n## Connection to existing work\n\n- META-121 (Bet 5) — C8 multi-node routing is the Bet 5 hardware-decision unblock\n- META-124 (integration cycles) — C2 integrator daemon already calls cost model implicitly via preflight; explicit chump disk plan call adds the safety guard\n- META-125 (consensus) — disk-aware decision for spawning N curators\n- META-127 (curator suite productization) — disk-watcher could be a new curator OR infra-watcher extension\n- INFRA-2125 (cargo-target-reaper) — already exists; disk plan can trigger on-demand reap\n- INFRA-2181 (reaper post-ship trigger) — sibling; disk plan can request emergency reap\n- INFRA-2188 (cargo-runner cache leak) — C2 inventory daemon catches this class structurally\n- INFRA-518 (fleet scaling gate) — existing scale-up criteria; C7 extends with disk dimension\n- DOC-063 (CI bottleneck review) — disk-aware fleet is one of the Lever 5 categories\n\n## Success criteria\n\n- Zero ENOSPC fleet crashes from chump-driven work (today's evidence: 0 in last hour with manual oversight; this would be structural)\n- Pre-claim refusal triggers correctly: when free < 5 GB, claim refuses with alternative\n- Fleet scaler adapts: when disk drops, fleet shrinks automatically before crisis\n- Multi-node ready: same machinery works on 1 node (today) or N nodes (Bet 5 future)\n- Operator surface: `chump disk status` answers \"can I run X right now\" in <1s\n\n## Open questions\n\n1. **Floor threshold** — 5 GB free (drafted) vs 10 GB? Bigger floor = more conservative, less work done.\n2. **Auto-scale aggressiveness** — auto-scale cron every 5 min (drafted) vs every 1 min? Trade off responsiveness vs noise.\n3. **Disk-watcher as new curator role** — fits META-127 productization vision; OR extend infra-watcher? My read: extend infra-watcher initially (faster), split out to dedicated curator when scope grows.\n4. **Cost model maintenance** — observability curator owns updates from measurement (drafted) OR auto-tuned from disk-cost-observed.jsonl? My read: auto-tune with operator-visible bounds.\n5. **Pre-claim refusal UX** — hard refuse (operator must reap manually) vs offer auto-reap (run reaper inline)? Auto-reap is convenient but slower.\n\n## Effort\n\n~1 week to Phase 1 (Layer 1 + Layer 2 + Layer 3 single-node). Multi-node depends on Bet 5 hardware decision."
  closed_date: '2026-06-05'
  closed_pr: 2744
  outcome_id: MISSION-010

- id: META-129
  domain: META
  title: "META: fleet-scrubber segment-detail info architecture — collab gap for tokens/cost/trace/multi-machine (INFRA-2164 followup)"
  status: open
  priority: P2
  effort: m
  description: |
    Collab gap to define the rich segment-detail panel of the fleet-scrubber (INFRA-2176, live at http://localhost:7070/scrubber/). Today the side panel shows only an events list + raw payload. To be Marcus-grade and operator-rich, we want token/cost overlay, subagent attribution fix, causal trace per PR, multi-machine consolidation, and a structured field list. This gap collects proposals from fleet curators via FEEDBACK broadcasts before AC are finalized.
  acceptance_criteria:
    - Collect at least 5 FEEDBACK responses from peer curators (or operator decisions) on the design proposals; record them in docs/design/SCRUBBER_PANEL_PROPOSALS.md
    - "Decision section: which fields land in v1 vs deferred to v2"
    - "Idle palette v1: segmenter promotes 'idle' from one state to five — scheduled-quiet (worker between iters, healthy), working-but-quiet (bash_call matches known-long cmds like cargo build / gh pr merge / sleep), stalled (heartbeat present but no event >5min, warning shade), dead (no heartbeat + no events >15min, dark shade), untracked (only a session_start emitted ever, hatched pattern). Each carries a confidence flag (solid when we have rich events, dashed when we are inferring from sparse signal)"
    - "Idle palette signals: drive from stale_gap_lock_protected reason=heartbeat_fresh (alive), bash_call cmd patterns (long-op detection), lease expiry timestamp, gap between events vs window size — no new event kinds required"
    - "Token/cost integration: recorder payload schema includes tokens_in tokens_out cost_usd model when source is anthropic-api; scrubber sums per segment and renders 'Cost' row in panel"
    - "Subagent attribution: at Agent-tool dispatch time emit kind=subagent_spawned with sub_session_id + worktree_path; recorder maps subsequent ambient events to sub_session_id by worktree path; scrubber renders sub-lanes nested under parent"
    - "Causal-trace mode: panel has 'Story of PR' tab querying /api/trace/pr/:n and renders timeline with cursor highlighting on the gantt"
    - "Multi-machine consolidation decision: option A (per-machine sqlite + server joins) or B (single shared sqlite via NATS replication) — pick one with rationale"
    - "UI correctness: segment duration computed from start_ts_ms/end_ts_ms (currently shows 0s after the INFRA-2189 normalization); panel surfaces last 3 events on either side of the segment window even when zero events fall inside (so it never says 'No events' for a real segment)"
    - "Marcus review: external-collab curator loops Marcus on the proposal doc and captures his design feedback before ship"
  depends_on: [INFRA-2164]
  outcome_id: MISSION-010

- id: META-130
  domain: META
  title: "META: sub-agent session attribution — Agent-tool dispatch emits kind=subagent_spawned, recorder maps by worktree path"
  status: open
  priority: P2
  effort: m
  description: |
    Sub-agents launched via Claude Code's Agent tool inherit the parent harness session_id when they emit to ambient.jsonl — so 3 Sonnets dispatched in parallel for INFRA-2174/2175/2176 all attributed their file_edit / bash_call events to the parent (chump-Chump-1776471708). On the fleet-scrubber this collapses 3 distinct workers into one lane, defeating the whole point. Fix in three parts: (a) at Agent-tool dispatch time, the orchestrator emits kind=subagent_spawned with sub_session_id + worktree_path; (b) the recorder maintains a worktree_path -> sub_session_id map and rewrites the session_id of subsequent events whose payload.worktree matches; (c) scrubber renders sub-lanes nested under the parent lane (indented label, dashed lane separator) so the hierarchy is visible. This is a non-trivial cross-cutting change; treating it as design-then-implement.
  acceptance_criteria:
    - Design proposal in docs/design/SUBAGENT_ATTRIBUTION.md covers the 3 parts above with rationale, signal flow, and edge cases (subagent crashes; parent ships before sub does; sub spawns sub-sub)
    - At least one harness (Claude Code orchestrator path) emits kind=subagent_spawned via chump-coord emit at Agent-tool dispatch — payload includes sub_session_id (synthetic), worktree_path, parent_session_id
    - crates/chump-fleet-recorder maintains an in-memory worktree-path -> sub_session_id map; on each ambient event with payload.worktree, rewrites session_id to the mapped sub-session before INSERT
    - "web/fleet-scrubber renders sub-lanes nested under parent: indented label, faint dashed separator between parent and its subs; collapsible expand/collapse arrow"
    - "Smoke test: dispatch a fixture event sequence with parent=A spawning sub=B; assert recorder stores B's events under B not A; assert scrubber renders A with B nested below"
    - Cross-references META-129 (scrubber design collab — sub-agent attribution is one of its open questions); resolves the open question in META-129 (b)
  depends_on: [META-129, INFRA-2164]
  outcome_id: MISSION-010

- id: META-131
  domain: META
  title: "EFFECTIVE P1 (CI ARCHITECT): collapse 12+ CI gates into 1 required 'verified' aggregator with path-aware lane-skip stubs + auto-flake-quarantine; eliminates admin-merge as routine hygiene (currently ~70% of today's merges needed bypass)"
  status: done
  priority: P1
  effort: xl
  acceptance_criteria:
    - "Rough shape (decompose at claim time):\n\n(a) **Inventory + audit doc** — docs/strategy/CI_POLICY_AUDIT.md catalogs every current check (required + visible), why it was added, what bug class it caught, current cost (time, flake rate)\n\n(b) **Architecture spec** — docs/design/CI_VERIFIED_AGGREGATOR.md proposes a SINGLE required 'verified' check that fans out path-aware lane checks; rules for stub-pass on path-skip; rules for flake-quarantine after N consecutive intermittent fails\n\n(c) **Replace required trio** — drop branch-protection + ruleset down to single 'verified' aggregator. Lane checks (audit, test, ACP, fast-checks, clippy, cargo-test, e2e-pwa) become inputs to 'verified', not required individually\n\n(d) **Path-filter correctness** — every required-lane check MUST emit even when path-filter excludes the real job (extends INFRA-2191 stub pattern to all lanes)\n\n(e) **Flake quarantine class** — when a test fails 3+ times consecutively across PRs with the same error fingerprint, auto-tag as 'flake' + skip in 'verified' aggregator + file follow-up gap; un-quarantine when fixed\n\n(f) **Cascade rebase auto-trigger** — when keystone file lands on main, auto-rebase all open PRs (extends INFRA-2207 + queue-driver.sh)\n\n(g) **Drop-and-restore safety** — every required-check edit emits ambient kind=ruleset_changed; watchdog alerts when required_status_checks empty >2min (INFRA-2201 dependency)\n\n(h) **Migration plan** — week 1: ship aggregator side-by-side with current; week 2: shadow-mode (aggregator runs but doesn't gate); week 3: flip aggregator to required, retire individual required-checks\n\nKey constraint: admin-merge MUST become emergency-only (current: ~70% of session merges); measure post-rollout target: <5% admin-merge ratio.\n\nDecomp via chump gap decompose at claim time — sub-gaps for (a) through (h) above"
    - 2. After decompose, sub-gaps inherit META-131 depends_on chain so they ship in order
    - "3. After full ship: 30-day measurement window — admin-merge ratio target <5%; if >10%, ROLLBACK partial and re-audit"
  notes: |
