- id: META-209
  domain: META
  title: AI-agent admin-merge protocol — dedicated bot identity + auto-trigger gate (N≥3 consensus votes + content-class allowlist + no T1-T4 escalation) + META-180 daemon integration; codifies the rule that just-ran in this session as durable infrastructure
  status: open
  priority: P2
  effort: m
  description: |
    OPERATOR QUESTION 2026-05-30T18:00Z (verbatim): 'WHY have we not given admin-merge access to an AI agent that has protocols'
    
    In this session, the orchestrator (Claude Opus) admin-merged 7 PRs in 6 minutes (18:09-18:15) under operator's ad-hoc authorization, using the operator's gh CLI auth. This worked but is NOT the durable answer — it depends on a human session being active and authorizing.
    
    The durable answer: a dedicated bot identity + auto-trigger gate + policy-allowlist for admin-merge, all gated by consensus. Substrate is mostly in place:
      - META-207 (just merged): T1/T2/T3/T4 escalation doctrine
      - INFRA-2274 (PR #2841, still queued): ConsensusCoordinator pre-merge gate
      - META-180 / META-181 (just merged): PR-shepherd daemon umbrella + skeleton
      - Broadcast/vote/deliberator: live
      - chump consensus-tally: spec'd
    
    What's missing (this gap closes):
      1. Dedicated bot identity ('chump-fleet-bot' GitHub account with constrained admin) so admin-merge doesn't depend on operator's PAT
      2. Auto-trigger daemon: scripts/coord/auto-admin-merge-daemon.sh that walks open PRs, checks fix-class allowlist + consensus quorum + no T1-T4 trigger, then issues 'gh pr merge --admin --squash' as the bot
      3. Policy file: docs/process/AUTO_ADMIN_MERGE_POLICY.md defining the IF conditions
      4. Integration with META-180 PR-shepherd daemon (admin-merge becomes an action the shepherd can take)
      5. Audit: each agent admin-merge emits kind=agent_admin_merge with role, pr_number, fix_class, consensus_corr_id, trigger_check_results
  acceptance_criteria:
