- id: RESILIENT-061
  domain: RESILIENT
  title: "RESILIENT: deliberator tick never emits consensus_result — bad-math crash blocks ALL fleet consensus"
  status: done
  priority: P1
  effort: s
  description: |
    Verified 2026-06-03 (operator-commissioned 'verify then deploy' of the A2A/consensus layer). consensus_result count in ambient.jsonl = 0, EVER. Running 'CHUMP_FLEET_RECV_SIDE_V0=1 bash scripts/coord/deliberator-loop.sh tick' prints '(eval): bad math expression: operator expected at 0' in the '## Pending proposals' loop and emits NO consensus_result. The tally CLI ('chump consensus-tally') works read-only and produces CORRECT verdicts (e.g. corr_id=audit-queue-wedge-20260603 verdict=NO_QUORUM), so the bug is NOT in the tally math — it is in the deliberator daemon's per-proposal EPOCH arithmetic (lines ~294-333: window_cutoff / line_epoch=_iso_to_epoch(ts) / deadline_epoch fed into bash (( )) with no numeric guard; one malformed/edge-case proposal ts poisons the batch). NET IMPACT: the fleet cannot reach automated consensus on ANY proposal — including the live ci-jail-out-without-bypass-2026-06-03 and audit-queue-wedge proposals it is currently using to decide how to escape CI jail. COMPOUNDING: 'chump vote' is gated off when CHUMP_FLEET_RECV_SIDE_V0 is unset (verified: 'feature flag off, vote not emitted'), so proposals also starve for quorum (only 1 of 12 inbox proposals has any votes). Secondary: the tick is O(all inbox lines x jq-fork-per-field) and timed out at 30s under trace — slow enough to miss its own cadence.
  acceptance_criteria:
    - CHUMP_FLEET_RECV_SIDE_V0=1 bash scripts/coord/deliberator-loop.sh tick runs to completion with no 'bad math expression' error
    - given a synthetic proposal whose votes meet quorum, the tick emits kind=consensus_result to ambient.jsonl (consensus_result count goes 0 -> >=1, verified end-to-end)
    - a malformed proposal ts (empty / fractional-seconds / non-ISO) is skipped gracefully via a numeric guard, NOT crashing the batch — one bad input must not poison the whole tick
    - new CI test scripts/ci/test-deliberator-tick-emits.sh feeds a quorum-meeting fixture and asserts consensus_result is emitted, and feeds a malformed-ts proposal and asserts no crash + no emission
    - the tick does not re-fork jq per field per line in a way that exceeds its schedule interval (bound the per-tick cost or document the window)
  notes: |
    [2026-06-04T00:06:13Z] confirmed merged on origin/main (fix/feat commit); registry hygiene
  closed_pr: 2992
  outcome_id: RESILIENT-000

- id: RESILIENT-062
  domain: RESILIENT
  title: "RESILIENT: deliberator scans prunable ambient.jsonl but proposals live in feedback.jsonl (53 vs 6) — consumer reads wrong file"
  status: done
  priority: P1
  effort: s
  description: |
    Verified 2026-06-03 (post RESILIENT-061 fix, while proving consensus end-to-end). PRODUCER/CONSUMER FILE MISMATCH: scripts/coord/broadcast.sh writes 'FEEDBACK kind=proposal' canonically to .chump-locks/feedback.jsonl (line 520, 'the dedicated feedback.jsonl that the curator reads' — INFRA-1272 territory). But scripts/coord/deliberator-loop.sh scans AMBIENT='${CHUMP_AMBIENT_LOG:-$LOCK_DIR/ambient.jsonl}' (line 64). Ground-truth counts: feedback.jsonl has 53 proposals, ambient.jsonl has 6. ambient.jsonl is the high-volume audit stream that the reaper/prune daemons trim, so proposals AGE OUT before the deliberator can tally them — and the durable proposal store (feedback.jsonl) is invisible to the consumer. This is INDEPENDENT of RESILIENT-061 (the bad-math crash, fixed in PR #2992): even with the tick fixed, it tallies only the fraction of proposals that survive in ambient, missing the canonical 53. Same producer/consumer wiring class as META-163 (fan-out globs sentinel files no producer creates). Design ref: docs/strategy/FLEET_RECV_SIDE_2026-05-30.md §3. Decision to make: either (a) point the deliberator scan at the durable feedback.jsonl, or (b) make broadcast.sh's proposal path reliably dual-write every proposal to a NON-pruned stream the deliberator reads. Prefer (a) — read the durable store, don't tally off an audit log that gets reaped.
  acceptance_criteria:
    - producer (broadcast.sh proposal path) and consumer (deliberator-loop.sh tick scan) agree on ONE durable proposal store — proposals are not tallied off the reaper-pruned ambient.jsonl
    - "a proposal emitted via 'broadcast.sh FEEDBACK kind=proposal' is visible to 'deliberator-loop.sh tick' and reaches tally (verify end-to-end: broadcast a test proposal, run tick, confirm it appears in the Pending-proposals scan)"
    - the deliberator no longer silently misses proposals that exist in feedback.jsonl but have been reaped from ambient.jsonl
    - new/extended CI test asserts a freshly-broadcast proposal is seen by the deliberator scan within its window (not dependent on ambient retention)
  depends_on: [RESILIENT-061]
  notes: |
    
    MISSION-010 Gate1 (consensus actually fires) — co-prioritized 2026-06-05: this is THE blocker making fleet consensus emit 0 verdicts ever; deliberator reads ambient.jsonl while FEEDBACK proposals live in feedback.jsonl. Mission-linked for picker boost.
  closed_pr: 3074
  outcome_id: RESILIENT-000

- id: RESILIENT-063
  domain: RESILIENT
  title: "RESILIENT P0: audit job cold-builds every run — per-run CARGO_TARGET_DIR + PR-scoped prefix defeat rust-cache → 15min timeout (the trunk SPOF)"
  status: open
  priority: P2
  effort: s
  description: |
    VERIFIED 2026-06-03 (operator: FIX IT). The required 'audit' job in .github/workflows/ci.yml (~line 1500) is the trunk SPOF — it times out at timeout-minutes:15, wedging the merge queue. ROOT CAUSE: the audit job has NO effective compile cache, so it cold-builds 'chump' on every run. Three independent defeaters: (1) env CARGO_TARGET_DIR=/tmp/cargo-target-<run_id> (line ~1529) redirects build output to a per-run /tmp path, but Swatinem/rust-cache@v2 (line ~1551) caches ./target with no cache-directories override telling it about /tmp -> restores an empty dir -> cold build; (2) rust-cache prefix-key is PR-scoped 'v1-pr-<number>' (line ~1556) -> zero cross-PR cache sharing -> every PR's first audit is cold; (3) RUSTC_WRAPPER/sccache is NOT set for audit (only cargo-test wires it), so the R2 sccache that INFRA-2504/#2984 provisioned never reaches audit. NET: audit cold-builds chump several times per run -> >15min -> timeout. This is why #2984's sccache restore did not fix the timeout (it never reached the audit job). NOT fixed by INFRA-2516 (concurrency, a band-aid that reintroduces INFRA-1852) nor by redoing INFRA-2504. The fix makes the EXISTING rust-cache effective + shared. Bootstrapping note: the fix PR's own first audit run is cold; a small timeout headroom bump lets it land, then warm runs are fast.
  acceptance_criteria:
    - "audit job's rust-cache actually caches the dir cargo builds into: either drop the per-run CARGO_TARGET_DIR override (build to ./target which rust-cache caches) OR add cache-directories so rust-cache caches the /tmp target"
