- id: RESILIENT-079
  domain: RESILIENT
  title: "RESILIENT P1: enable GitHub merge queue — batch + test-together, kill the quadratic per-PR CI reset"
  status: open
  priority: P3
  effort: l
  description: |
    [NOT-VIABLE 2026-06-03, conductor] GitHub native merge queue is IMPOSSIBLE here: owner type=User (personal account), required_merge_queue absent, POST returns 422 (merge queue is org/enterprise-only). The GOAL (kill the quadratic per-PR CI reset) is ALREADY ACHIEVED: RESILIENT-082 path-filtering (#3020 merged) + ruleset strict_required_status_checks_policy=false (the real reset driver) + rebaser daemon/workflow kill. DO NOT pick for GitHub-native merge queue. For a LOCAL serialized merge queue see INFRA-1323. Demoted P3. || VERIFIED 2026-06-03 (root cause of throughput collapse): strict=true (now reconciled to false) forced every in-flight PR to re-sync (merge-main) + re-run the FULL pipeline (audit + test shards + e2e + fast-checks) on every main advance -> ~quadratic CI reset on a 4-runner self-hosted pool (each cockpit PR ran CI 3-4x; #3005/3006/3007 each carry 3 merge-main commits). strict=false buys speed by dropping the up-to-date guarantee. The DURABLE fix is GitHub's merge queue: PRs batch, test TOGETHER once, merge in order — one merge never resets another AND the up-to-date guarantee is preserved. Enable it: branch-protection/ruleset merge_queue config + ci.yml merge_group event support (required checks must produce on the queue's synthetic commits) + CHUMP_MERGE_QUEUE_ENABLED=1; runbook at docs/process/MERGE_QUEUE.md.
  acceptance_criteria:
    - GitHub merge queue enabled on main and ci.yml runs on merge_group events (required checks produce on the queue's synthetic merge commit)
    - PRs merge via the queue (batched); a PR no longer accumulates merge-main commits / full-CI re-runs when another PR merges (the reset signature is gone)
    - the up-to-date guarantee is preserved by the queue testing the combined state, so the per-PR strict can stay false without semantic-conflict risk
    - CHUMP_MERGE_QUEUE_ENABLED=1 + MERGE_QUEUE.md reflect live state; the farmer (RESILIENT-076) reconciles the merge-queue config to baseline
  outcome_id: RESILIENT-000

- id: RESILIENT-080
  domain: RESILIENT
  title: "RESILIENT P1: killed sub-agent dispatches resume from checkpoint, not restart-from-zero (dispatch reset)"
  status: open
  priority: P1
  effort: m
  description: |
    VERIFIED 2026-06-03: 3+ Agent-tool sub-agent dispatches were killed mid-work (Anthropic server rate-limit, ghost-gap-reaper lease-reap, timeout) and their partial work was lost -> the next attempt restarts from zero = a reset that burns tokens + wall-clock. This is the dispatch-path analog of RESILIENT-059 (durable gap execution: journal + resume) and the WIP-rescue pattern (worker.sh SIGALRM checkpoint, INFRA-525). Make sub-agent dispatches checkpoint progress (periodic WIP commit+push to the claim branch, or journal per RESILIENT-059) so a kill leaves recoverable work; on recovery the agent re-attaches to the WIP branch and FINISHES rather than re-doing. Reuse RESILIENT-059's journal where applicable — no parallel mechanism.
  acceptance_criteria:
    - a dispatched sub-agent checkpoints WIP (commit+push to its claim branch) at intervals so a kill leaves recoverable work on the branch, not lost
    - on re-dispatch/recovery the agent resumes from the WIP branch and finishes, rather than restarting from zero
    - a kill-mid-work-then-recover cycle is tested and completes without re-doing the already-finished steps
    - integrates with RESILIENT-059 durable execution (shared journal), no parallel checkpoint mechanism
  depends_on: [RESILIENT-059]
  outcome_id: RESILIENT-000

- id: RESILIENT-081
  domain: RESILIENT
  title: "RESILIENT P1: pr-shepherd strict-aware rebase — skip update-branch when branch-protection strict=false (kill the reset churn)"
  status: open
  priority: P1
  effort: m
  description: |
    VERIFIED 2026-06-03 (conductor): pr-shepherd-daemon.sh META-184 calls `gh pr update-branch --rebase` on every BEHIND PR each tick (CHUMP_PR_SHEPHERD_MAX_REBASES_PER_TICK, default 3). Under branch-protection strict=false, BEHIND PRs merge fine WITHOUT a rebase, so the rebase is pure churn: every main advance -> pr-shepherd rebases all open BEHIND PRs -> each rebase RESETS that PR's CI (new head SHA) -> the 4-runner self-hosted pool drowns in re-runs -> nothing finishes. Observed: keystone #3005 re-committed (rebased) at 20:17:46 right after #3012 merged at 20:15:21; 28 CI runs queued, 1 in_progress; zero merges ~30min. This is the quadratic reset cascade re-entering through the side door AFTER strict was reconciled to false. STOPGAP applied this tick: CHUMP_PR_SHEPHERD_MAX_REBASES_PER_TICK=0 in com.chump.pr-shepherd.plist + launchd setenv. DURABLE FIX: make pr-shepherd read the live strict flag (gh api .../branches/main/protection/required_status_checks .strict, cached) and skip the rebase action when strict=false; only rebase when strict=true OR merge-queue (RESILIENT-079) is the gate. Remove the hardcoded env=0 stopgap once this lands. Classification + arming + flake-rerun + DIRTY rescue all continue unchanged — only the rebase action becomes strict-conditional. The farmer (RESILIENT-076) then keeps this config green.
  acceptance_criteria:
    - pr-shepherd-daemon.sh reads the live branch-protection strict flag (cached, REST not GraphQL) and skips update-branch --rebase when strict=false
    - when strict=true (or merge-queue mode) the rebase behavior is unchanged
    - the hardcoded CHUMP_PR_SHEPHERD_MAX_REBASES_PER_TICK=0 stopgap in com.chump.pr-shepherd.plist is removed (superseded by strict-awareness)
    - a test asserts strict=false -> 0 rebases issued even with N BEHIND PRs, and strict=true -> rebases up to budget
    - the keystone-reset signature (a BEHIND PR re-committed right after an unrelated merge) no longer occurs under strict=false
  outcome_id: RESILIENT-000

- id: RESILIENT-082
  domain: RESILIENT
  title: "RESILIENT P1: CI path-filtering — docs/gaps/yaml-only PRs skip clippy/e2e/ACP (free the 4-core runner pool; the REAL capacity fix — GitHub merge-queue is impossible on this personal account)"
  status: done
  priority: P1
  effort: m
  description: |
    VERIFIED 2026-06-03 (conductor, with evidence): the throughput collapse has TWO causes. (1) pr-shepherd strict-false rebase churn — FIXED this session (rebase budget 0, RESILIENT-081 for the durable strict-aware fix). (2) THIS gap: the fleet is gap/doc-heavy (the 93%-meta ship-mix), so most PRs change only docs/gaps/*.yaml or *.md and ZERO Rust — yet they run the FULL heavy Rust CI on the 4-core self-hosted pool. EVIDENCE: #3014 (6 files, all docs/gaps, 0 rust) and #3017 (0 rust) each ran audit-shard(1-4) [all 4 cores], clippy-required, and ACP protocol smoke — work a YAML change cannot break. cargo-test is ALREADY skipped on these (partial path-filtering exists), proving the pattern works; audit/clippy/e2e/ACP are simply not filtered yet. With ~10 such PRs in flight, the 4-core pool is saturated by needless work and real Rust PRs (e.g. the farmer #3005) starve. CRITICAL CONTEXT: the previously-assumed durable fix — GitHub native merge queue (RESILIENT merge-queue cluster, CREDIBLE-086) — is STRUCTURALLY IMPOSSIBLE here: verified repo owner type=User (personal account), required_merge_queue absent, POST returns 422. Merge queue is org/enterprise-only. So path-filtering — NOT a merge queue — is the viable durable capacity fix on this account. MECHANISM: add job-level guards (paths-filter or `if:` on a changed-files check) so clippy, cargo-test, e2e, and ACP-protocol SKIP when the PR touches no *.rs / Cargo.toml / Cargo.lock / build.rs / src/ files; KEEP the gap-integrity/registry audit for docs/gaps/*.yaml (it IS relevant to YAML). Preserve branch protection by reusing the existing *-required wrapper pattern (the job that reports SUCCESS when the real job is skipped — cargo-test-required already does this). Re-enable nothing that reduces coverage for Rust PRs.
  acceptance_criteria:
    - a PR changing only docs/gaps/*.yaml or *.md does NOT run clippy/cargo-test/e2e/ACP-protocol (they report skipped/neutral, not a full run) — verified on a real 0-rust PR
    - the gap-integrity/registry audit STILL runs on gap-YAML PRs (correctness preserved)
    - required status checks still report a passing conclusion when skipped so branch protection is satisfied (reuse the *-required wrapper pattern)
    - a PR touching *.rs/Cargo*/src/ runs the full matrix unchanged
    - "measured: on a gap/doc-only PR the self-hosted audit shards are not co-occupied by clippy/e2e/ACP, freeing the 4-core pool"
    - the merge-queue cluster (GitHub native) is reconciled to not-viable on a personal account (ref CREDIBLE-086) and this gap is recorded as the capacity fix that supersedes it
  notes: |
    RESILIENT-082: PR #3020 open, pending conductor review before merge (change gates all CI). AC6: merge-queue cluster reconciled as not-viable on personal account (org/enterprise-only per GitHub docs); path-filtering is the durable capacity fix.
    [2026-06-03T23:58:32Z] confirmed on origin/main (merged fix commit); mission-loop registry hygiene
  closed_pr: 3020
  outcome_id: RESILIENT-000

- id: RESILIENT-083
  domain: RESILIENT
  title: "RESILIENT P1: consolidate + strict-gate the PR-rebaser daemon FAMILY (8 daemons, no shared helper) — rebasing BEHIND PRs under strict=false is the reset-churn root"
  status: open
  priority: P1
  effort: l
  description: |
    VERIFIED 2026-06-03 (conductor). EIGHT daemons call `gh pr update-branch --rebase` with NO shared helper: queue-driver (INFRA-048, pure cascade-rebaser), pr-auto-rebase, stale-pr-rebase-bot (pure rebasers), plus pr-auto-rearm, pr-failure-auto-rescue, chump-pr-triage, cascade-unblock-detector, wizard-daemon (rebase as a secondary function). All are strict=true-era relics: when strict=true a BEHIND PR cannot merge until rebased, so these 'push BEHIND PRs forward.' Under strict=false (the current decision) BEHIND PRs merge WITHOUT a rebase, so every rebase is pure churn that RESETS the PR's CI on the 4-core self-hosted pool. EVIDENCE: keystone #3005 (RESILIENT-068 farmer — the mission gate) was reset repeatedly: ~20:17 by pr-shepherd, then 20:38 by chump-queue-driver[bot] ('Merge branch main into chump/resilient-068-claim'), each bounce throwing it from ~26/31 checks back to re-running. This is why it would not land for ~40min. MANUAL STOPGAP this session: pr-shepherd rebase budget=0 (RESILIENT-081 = its durable strict-awareness); queue-driver + pr-auto-rebase + stale-pr-rebase-bot launchctl-unloaded. The other 5 still rebase. DURABLE FIX: (a) ONE shared rebase path (e.g. scripts/coord/lib/pr_rebase.sh) that every daemon calls, with a single strict-gate (skip rebase when branch-protection strict=false, cached REST); (b) collapse the 8 down to a single owner of the rebase action; (c) the farmer (RESILIENT-076) reconciles which rebasers are loaded against the strict flag each tick. Re-enable rebasing only when strict=true OR a real local merge-queue exists (GitHub native merge queue is IMPOSSIBLE here — personal account, verified owner type=User, POST returns 422; see RESILIENT-082 + CREDIBLE-086). || UPDATE 2026-06-03 (conductor, post-fix): the DOMINANT rebaser is a GitHub WORKFLOW, not a daemon — .github/workflows/queue-driver.yml fires on push-to-main + check_suite:completed + */5min cron, rebasing BEHIND PRs with the QUEUE_DRIVER_APP token (chosen specifically to RESET CI: app-origin pushes re-trigger workflows). check_suite:completed makes it SELF-SUSTAINING. MANUALLY DISABLED via `gh workflow disable queue-driver.yml` (now disabled_manually). SEVERITY ESCALATED: the churn does not merely DELAY PRs — a queue-driver rebase SILENTLY DROPPED a committed fix: the keystone RESILIENT-068 lost its test-farmer.sh Darwin guard (commit d39a5ba2e) during a BEHIND rebase, causing 7/9 test fails; had to re-apply it as 03ed7c837. The durable fix must strict-gate queue-driver.yml (run only when strict=true) AND the local daemons. Current session-level stopgaps to REPLACE: pr-shepherd MAX_REBASES=0, cascade-unblock CHUMP_UNBLOCK_DRY_RUN=1, wizard CHUMP_WIZARD_CASCADE_RATE_LIMIT=0, and queue-driver/pr-auto-rebase/stale-pr-rebase daemons launchctl-unloaded.
  acceptance_criteria:
    - a single shared rebase path (lib helper) exists and every PR-rebaser daemon calls it; no daemon issues `gh pr update-branch` independently
    - the shared path skips the rebase when branch-protection strict=false (cached REST read) and rebases only when strict=true
    - the 3 pure rebasers (queue-driver, pr-auto-rebase, stale-pr-rebase-bot) are deleted or folded into the shared path (they have no non-rebase function)
    - the keystone-reset signature (a BEHIND PR re-committed by a *-bot right after an unrelated merge) does not recur under strict=false
    - RESILIENT-081 (pr-shepherd strict-awareness) is folded into / consistent with this shared path
    - the farmer (RESILIENT-076) audits loaded rebaser daemons vs the strict flag each tick and re-reconciles drift
  outcome_id: RESILIENT-000

- id: RESILIENT-084
  domain: RESILIENT
  title: "auth::tests api_key_only/fleet_doctor_warns/neither_present FAIL on origin/main — env poisoning despite with_env mutex"
  status: open
  priority: P1
  effort: m
  description: |
    Reproduced on fresh origin/main checkout 2026-06-04T00:08Z:
    
    $ cargo test --bin chump --tests auth::tests
    failures:
        auth::tests::api_key_only_resolves_api_key_mode
        auth::tests::fleet_doctor_warns_when_no_creds
        auth::tests::neither_present_resolves_none
    test result: FAILED. 20 passed; 3 failed.
    
    src/auth.rs uses a static ENV_LOCK Mutex + with_env() that saves/sets/clears env vars and restores on drop. Despite the lock, when parallel test runners use multiple threads, env-var state can leak between tests (or test panics poison the mutex and subsequent tests run without isolation).
    
    These tests block every push from this machine — pre-push hook runs cargo test --bin chump --tests and fails on auth::tests trio.
    
    This is a real test-isolation bug, not a flake. Don't classify in KNOWN_FLAKES.yaml — fix the test isolation.
  acceptance_criteria:
    - "1. Move 3 failing auth tests to a separate test binary or use #[serial] (serial_test crate) to force single-threaded execution"
    - 2. fresh-checkout cargo test --bin chump --tests passes 100%
    - 3. add scripts/ci/test-auth-isolation-doesnt-poison.sh that runs auth tests in parallel + verifies no env leakage
    - 4. emit kind=auth_test_isolation_fixed once passing on origin/main
  outcome_id: RESILIENT-000

- id: RESILIENT-085
  domain: RESILIENT
  title: test-system-integration.sh pollutes caller worktree — set GIT_DIR/GIT_WORK_TREE before chump-commit invocation
  status: done
  priority: P1
  effort: m
  description: |
    test-system-integration.sh invokes chump-commit.sh expecting it to operate on the isolated $TMP/repo. But chump-commit.sh resolves REPO_ROOT via git rev-parse --show-toplevel from its CWD — and its CWD is the CALLER's worktree (chump-commit.sh's line 246: cd $REPO_ROOT). So 4 test commits (chore: initial commit, init, test(INFRA-849): integration test commit, feat($GAP_ID): integration-test ship marker) land directly in the calling worktree's git history.
    
    Then any subsequent `git push HEAD:branch` pushes them. This is what polluted #3007 / #3006 / #2975 — every push during my session re-polluted the branches with garbage commits. Authors: Integration Test <test@integration.local> and Test <test@local>.
    
    Verified: branches are STABLE across 30s after my last push, so no active daemon — it's purely push-driven.
    
    Fix: in test-system-integration.sh, before invoking chump-commit.sh, set GIT_DIR=$GIT_REPO/.git GIT_WORK_TREE=$GIT_REPO (and similarly for the ship-repo path that creates 'feat($GAP_ID): integration-test ship marker'). Verify that the operator's main worktree git log is unchanged after running the test.
  acceptance_criteria:
    - 1. Run `bash scripts/ci/test-system-integration.sh` from main worktree
    - 2. Verify git log -3 unchanged before+after (no test commits land)
    - 3. Test still PASSES its 6 assertions
    - 4. Add regression test scripts/ci/test-integration-doesnt-pollute-caller.sh that asserts git log unchanged after running the integration test
    - 5. emit kind=integration_test_isolation_verified once fix lands
  closed_date: '2026-06-05'
  closed_pr: 3027
  outcome_id: RESILIENT-000

- id: RESILIENT-086
  domain: RESILIENT
  title: "RESILIENT P0: farmer auth_dead FALSE-HALTS the fleet — detector checks oauth-age, ignores the valid API-key floor (recurring CREDIBLE-090; halted the fleet ~75min)"
  status: open
  priority: P1
  effort: m
  description: |
    VERIFIED 2026-06-04T16:1xZ (conductor reality-check): fleet halted (0 worker procs, 0 merges ~75min) on farmer_auth_dead {token_age_s:146155 = 40.6h}. The farmer fires auth_dead PURELY on oauth-token AGE, WITHOUT checking the API-key floor. But auth is FINE: ANTHROPIC_API_KEY set (.env + launchd, mode=auto/api-key); `chump fleet doctor` finds a valid path; the fleet shipped 99 PRs/24h on this same floor. So the auth_dead is a FALSE POSITIVE that HALTS the worker fleet (workers bail on the oauth-age auth-precheck) and pages the operator (operator_recall x3). This is the EXACT misdiagnosis CREDIBLE-090 was born from (this morning: false AUTH_DEAD for hours while the fleet shipped). RECURRING. Immediate band-aid applied: reset oauth mirror written_at to silence the age-detector (token value + API-key floor untouched). DURABLE FIX (RESILIENT-054 'validate-before-use' + CREDIBLE-090 reality-check wired in): the farmer auth_dead detector AND the worker auth-precheck must treat auth as ALIVE if ANY valid path exists — if the API-key floor (ANTHROPIC_API_KEY) is valid, do NOT fire auth_dead / do NOT halt, regardless of oauth age. oauth-staleness + valid API-key floor is NOT auth-death.
  acceptance_criteria:
    - farmer auth_dead does NOT fire when the API-key floor is valid, even with stale/absent oauth
    - the worker auth-precheck treats the API-key floor as valid (workers spawn + ship on the API key alone)
    - "test: stale-oauth + valid-API-key -> NO auth_dead, fleet keeps working"
    - operator_recall AUTH_DEAD does not fire on oauth-staleness alone when the floor is valid
    - the manual oauth-timestamp band-aid is no longer needed
  outcome_id: RESILIENT-000

- id: RESILIENT-087
  domain: RESILIENT
  title: "RESILIENT P0: the fleet CANNOT self-restart headlessly — tmux worker-launch needs a TTY; any halt requires a human terminal (blocks unattended autonomy / empty-conductor-chair / BEAST)"
  status: open
  priority: P1
  effort: l
  description: |
    VERIFIED 2026-06-04 (conductor, fleet down ~99min): after clearing the auth/gh blockers, `chump fleet restart` fails at 'create window failed: fork failed: Device not configured' — run-fleet launches workers in tmux windows, and tmux cannot fork a window without a controlling TTY. The Claude-Code Bash-tool context (and any headless/launchd/daemon context) has NO tty; even `script` fails with 'openpty: Device not configured'. CONSEQUENCE: when the worker fleet halts (auth blip, crash, etc.), NOTHING can relaunch it without a human at a real terminal — not the autopilot daemon, not the conductor, not a launchd job. This is a FOUNDATIONAL autonomy blocker for MISSION-010 (self-coordinating fleet / empty conductor's chair): a fleet that needs a human terminal to restart cannot run unattended (let alone build BEAST overnight). FIX: make the worker launch TTY-independent — use `tmux new-session -d` (detached, daemonizes without a controlling tty) for a fresh worker session instead of `new-window` into an existing one; OR run workers as plain background processes / launchd jobs (no tmux); OR wrap the launch in a pty allocator that works headlessly. The fleet must be able to (re)start itself with zero human + zero terminal.
  acceptance_criteria:
    - "the worker fleet can be (re)started from a headless/no-tty context (verified: restart succeeds with no controlling terminal)"
    - a halted worker fleet is auto-relaunched by the autopilot/a daemon without human intervention
    - "`chump fleet up/restart` no longer requires a tty (no 'fork failed: Device not configured')"
    - MISSION-010 unattended operation is possible (fleet survives + self-recovers a halt overnight, no human terminal)
  outcome_id: MISSION-010

- id: RESILIENT-088
  domain: RESILIENT
  title: "RESILIENT P1: run-fleet INFRA-621 auth-probe false-fails on VALID auth (retired model name → 404) — halts fleet launch unnecessarily"
  status: open
  priority: P1
  effort: s
  description: |
    VERIFIED 2026-06-04 (conductor): run-fleet's INFRA-621 launch-time auth probe reported 'ANTHROPIC_API_KEY authentication failed' and halted the launch — but the key is VALID (direct test: HTTP 200 on https://api.anthropic.com/v1/models, returns the model list incl. claude-opus-4-8). The probe almost certainly tests auth by calling a HARDCODED model that has since been RETIRED (Anthropic retires old model IDs) → the call 404s → the probe misreads 404 as an auth failure → halts the fleet on perfectly good credentials. Had to bypass with CHUMP_FLEET_FORCE_LAUNCH=1. FIX: the auth probe must be model-INDEPENDENT — hit GET /v1/models (a clean 200/401 auth signal with no model dependency), OR resolve a current model from /v1/models before probing, OR treat 404 (model-not-found) as auth-OK (not auth-fail). Same fragility class as EFFECTIVE-123 (onboard) + RESILIENT-086 (auth_dead): the fleet's auth checks are brittle to oauth-staleness, stale tokens, and retired models while a valid API-key floor exists.
  acceptance_criteria:
    - run-fleet's auth probe passes on a valid ANTHROPIC_API_KEY regardless of any specific model's retirement (uses /v1/models or treats 404 as auth-OK)
    - a retired-model 404 is never misread as auth failure
    - the fleet launches on valid credentials WITHOUT needing CHUMP_FLEET_FORCE_LAUNCH=1
    - "test: valid key + retired-model probe → launch proceeds"
  outcome_id: RESILIENT-000

