- id: RESILIENT-103
  domain: RESILIENT
  title: "RESILIENT: a lease has THREE sources of truth (state.db leases + NATS-KV atomic claim + git claim-branch) with no reconciler — claim/release/reclaim/reaper-recovery must agree across all three"
  status: open
  priority: P1
  effort: m
  description: |
    Surfaced recovering from the INFRA-2744 ship (2026-06-05). A single interactive claim writes the lease to THREE independent stores: (1) the .chump/state.db 'leases' table, (2) the NATS-KV atomic claim (FLEET-034, chump-coord), (3) the git branch chump/<gap>-claim. They do NOT reconcile, and no tool clears all three. When the stale-worktree-reaper ate my worktree (RESILIENT-099), recovering the claim required THREE manual commands in sequence: 'sqlite3 .chump/state.db DELETE FROM leases WHERE gap_id=X' (state.db row persisted), 'git branch -D chump/X-claim' (branch lingered, blocking re-claim), and 'chump-coord release X' (NATS-KV claim blocked re-claim with 'NATS KV conflict'). 'chump --release --session <S> --force' did NOT clear any of them — it released a DIFFERENT (current-shell) session. INFRA-2744 fixed only the bot-merge-READS-state.db leg; this is the broader WRITE/RELEASE/RECONCILE unification across all three stores.
  acceptance_criteria:
    - "one lease abstraction (extend scripts/lib/lease.sh + the Rust atomic_claim) is the single API: claim writes state.db + NATS-KV + branch atomically; release clears all three; reclaim reads one canonical source"
    - "chump --release [--session S "
    - " --gap G] clears BOTH the state.db leases row AND the NATS-KV atomic claim (today it reliably clears neither; --session targets the wrong session)"
    - recovering an abandoned/reaped claim is ONE documented command, not the three-command manual sequence above
    - "regression test: claim a gap, release it, assert ZERO residue in all three stores (state.db leases row gone, NATS-KV key gone, no orphan branch blocking re-claim)"
  notes: |
    Sibling of INFRA-2744 (bot-merge read-leg, done) and RESILIENT-099 (reaper recovery surfaced this). The git-branch leg lingering after worktree reap is what forced 'git branch -D' before re-claim. Evidence in this session's transcript / ambient 2026-06-05T13:3x. The triple-store split is the root tax behind the whole 'interactive-claim-then-ship is painful' class (project_interactive_ship_friction memory).
    MISSION-010 Gate0 cluster — co-prioritized 2026-06-05; mission-linked for the MISSION-011 picker boost (mission_rank=0 → sorts ahead of non-mission gaps within its priority band).
  outcome_id: RESILIENT-000

- id: RESILIENT-104
  domain: RESILIENT
  title: "RESILIENT: ~9 fleet daemons crash-loop SILENTLY (integrator-daemon exit=127, ~8 daemons exit=78) while bootstrap --check reports them healthy — silently-dead-but-reported-alive; no chump verb surfaces last-exit"
  status: open
  priority: P1
  effort: s
  description: |
    2026-06-05 daemon inventory (launchctl list | grep chump → 95 loaded) showed com.chump.integrator-daemon last_exit=127 (command-not-found — this is the 'integrator daemon unhealthy' that bot-merge fell-open on during the INFRA-2744 ship) and ~8 daemons last_exit=78 (EX_CONFIG: curator-supervisor, main-health-watchdog, fleet-recorder, auto-merge-rearm, overnight-research, transient-retrigger, soak-checkpoint, github-liaison...). They are launchd-loaded (some KeepAlive), so chump-fleet-bootstrap.sh --check reports them registered/present and every liveness check reads GREEN — but they exit non-zero on EVERY run, doing nothing. This is the 'silently-dead-but-reported-alive' class: the dashboard says healthy while the work isn't happening. No chump verb surfaces it — I had to read raw launchctl. Bootstrap --check verifies REGISTRATION, not last-exit-status.
  acceptance_criteria:
    - chump daemons --status [--json] lists every fleet daemon with last-exit-code + crash-loop flag (non-zero last exit AND recent restart) + last-heartbeat age; harness-neutral (launchd now, structured for systemd later)
    - chump-fleet-bootstrap.sh --check and/or fleet-doctor-strict FAILS or WARNS when a required daemon's last exit is non-zero — today the integrator-daemon=127 + exit=78 cohort pass as healthy; they must not
    - the specific crash-loopers found 2026-06-05 (integrator-daemon=127 + the exit=78 cohort) are root-caused and fixed OR de-registered if obsolete (a crash-looping daemon lies; it is worse than an absent one)
    - a detector emits a daemon_crash_loop signal when a daemon exits non-zero N times in a window, surfaced in ambient + the fleet brief
  notes: |
    MISSION-010 Gate0 (substrate trustworthy / self-heals from HARM, not just death). Sibling of RESILIENT-099/100/103 (the farm fighting the operator this session). com.chump.daemon-exit-loop-watcher (INFRA-2417) + daemon-silence-monitor (INFRA-2352) exist — verify whether they already catch this class and just aren't surfaced, or have a hole that lets exit=78/127 pass. Faces the chump daemons --status verb in EFFECTIVE-178. Evidence: this session's launchctl snapshot.
    [2026-06-05 reframe] NOT a clean build — the detector + doctor-gate ALREADY EXIST: daemon-exit-loop-watcher-daemon.sh (INFRA-2417, detects consecutive non-zero exits + files P0) and fleet-doctor-strict.sh (daemon last-exit!=0 check). Yet integrator-daemon=127 + the exit=78 cohort persist 37h+. So the real task is: DEBUG why the existing detector isn't catching/surfacing these (is the watcher itself running? is it one of the exit=78 crash-loopers? threshold too high? gaps filed-but-invisible?), then fix. AC1 (chump daemons --status) can wrap the existing watcher's output. Do NOT build a parallel daemons-status (META-063 dup).
  outcome_id: RESILIENT-000

