- id: RESILIENT-131
  domain: RESILIENT
  title: "RESILIENT: fleet cannot self-rescue — autonomous workers leave PRs BLOCKED on their own red CI + die mid-task; L6 (058/059/060) marked done but NOT load-bearing"
  status: open
  priority: P1
  effort: l
  description: |
    VERIFIED 2026-06-08 (using the fleet's own record): autonomous claim→ship completion rate ≈ 0. Two failure modes: (A) worker implements + opens PR but it fails its OWN CI (trunk green) and the worker can't fix it → PR sits BLOCKED indefinitely (live: CREDIBLE-107 PR #3095, test/audit/fast-checks red, auto-merge armed but never fires, 2 days; gap stuck status=in_progress). (B) worker dies mid-task before committing → lease expires → status reverts to open, worktree leaks (live: RESILIENT-100, 1 uncommitted file, 0 commits). The promised fix (L6: RESILIENT-058 supervision / 059 durable-exec / 060 guardrail) is marked DONE but NOT load-bearing: 0 gap_supervisor_escalated events ever, no durable journal store/tables exist, none referenced in worker.sh/run-fleet.sh, and the failures they claim to handle still occur. The acute mode (worker fixes its own red CI) was never in any L6 AC. Real throughput today is manual/Opus bypass ships (opus-in-a-trench-coat). Rough shape (decompose at claim): (a) wire RESILIENT-058 supervisor into the worker path + verify it fires; (b) build/wire RESILIENT-059 durable journal + verify resume; (c) NEW CI-self-rescue loop — a worker (or rescue agent) iterates on its own red CI until green or escalates with a diagnosis; (d) the outcome test.
  acceptance_criteria:
    - "OUTCOME (the real DoD, not a signal): autonomous end-to-end completion rate > 0 — at least one gap goes claim→implement→CI-green→merge with NO human/Opus/bypass intervention, proven by a merged PR with NO Bot-Merge-Bypass trailer from an autonomous worker session."
    - "CI-self-rescue: when a worker PR is BLOCKED on its OWN failing CI (trunk green), a loop diagnoses + fixes until checks pass, OR escalates with a concrete diagnosis and moves the gap to a real blocked state — it does NOT sit in_progress/BLOCKED indefinitely. Reproduce + clear the CREDIBLE-107 #3095 class."
    - "RESILIENT-058 supervision is load-bearing: a retry-storm on a real gap emits gap_supervisor_escalated and sets status=blocked (currently 0 such events ever). Wired into worker.sh/run-fleet.sh."
    - "RESILIENT-059 durable resume is load-bearing: the journal store exists and a worker killed mid-gap resumes from it (no revert+leak). Reproduce + clear the RESILIENT-100 class (no orphan worktree)."
    - "The three L6 gaps (058/059/060) are reconciled: reopened or superseded by this gap, with their mechanisms verified firing — not left marked done while non-functional."

- id: RESILIENT-132
  domain: RESILIENT
  title: "RESILIENT: bot-merge interactive ship non-viable on degraded substrate (9 failure modes; lease corrupts every cycle)"
  status: open
  priority: P1
  effort: m
  description: |
    Shipping CREDIBLE-128 (a verified test-fix) via bot-merge hit 9 distinct failures, proving interactive manual shipping is non-viable on the current degraded substrate. (1) silent wedge: an early crash orphans the heartbeat subshell which holds the output pipe open, so the run LOOKS alive but is dead; (2) import-not-found: a freshly-claimed worktree lacks the gap YAML/state.db entry; (3) ID collision: stale local state.db handed out CREDIBLE-127 which was closed on origin/main; (4) preflight cargo-test exceeds its 300s budget (INFRA-1422) on a cold worktree under build contention; (5) the stage-timeout SIGTERM releases the lease; (6) re-claim fails worktree/branch-exists; (7) re-claim hits a ghost NATS-KV claim (chump-coord status shows 0 refs but chump claim conflicts); (8) chump gap import returns fatal non-zero whenever pre-existing title-similar fixture dups (INFRA-002/race-a, INFRA-1268) are present, which bot-merge treats as a claim failure; (9) bot-merge HANGS after Tests-passed before push with no children and no network = a non-tty-safe read/stdin hang (RESILIENT-121 class). Root: bot-merge/claim/lease are fragile to interactive ops and re-corrupt the lease every cycle; the fleet survives identical wedges via farmer/paramedic/watchdog recovery. Adjacent rot: integrator-daemon launchd job is exit-127, main-preflight-watchdog state 116h stale. Verified CREDIBLE-128 code preserved at branch credible-128-work (9d2e933d4).
  acceptance_criteria:
    - bot-merge push/post-test stages are non-tty-safe (stdin from /dev/null) so they never hang headless
    - bot-merge preflight pre-builds the test target or uses a contention-aware budget so cold worktrees do not trip the 300s stage timeout
    - chump gap import is non-fatal (warn not error) on pre-existing title-similar fixture dups so it never blocks claim
    - a bot-merge stage timeout does NOT release the gap lease
    - integrator-daemon launchd job runs cleanly (no exit-127)

- id: RESILIENT-133
  domain: RESILIENT
  title: "RESILIENT: bot-merge per-stage budget — global 300s stage-watchdog SIGTERMs cold cargo-test/clippy mid-compile"
  status: open
  priority: P1
  effort: m
  description: |
    bot-merge stage_start() (scripts/coord/bot-merge.sh) launches a per-stage budget watchdog that SIGTERMs bot-merge after a single global CHUMP_BOT_MERGE_STAGE_BUDGET_S (default 300s) regardless of stage. But cargo test (its run_timed_hb gtimeout is 1200s) and cargo clippy (900s) legitimately exceed 300s on a cold worktree, so the watchdog kills them mid-compile, emits botmerge_wedged, releases the lease, and forces a fragile re-claim. Observed shipping CREDIBLE-128: cargo-test stage exceeded budget 300s at elapsed 300s mid-compile on a fresh worktree. Fix: stage_start takes an optional per-stage budget as positional arg 2, defaulting to the current global; set cargo-test=1200 and both clippy stages=900 to match their gtimeouts. Backward-compatible (unspecified stages keep 300s).
  acceptance_criteria:
    - "stage_start() accepts an optional per-stage budget as positional arg 2, defaulting to CHUMP_BOT_MERGE_STAGE_BUDGET_S:-300 (backward-compatible)"
    - cargo test stage budget set to 1200s matching its run_timed_hb gtimeout
    - both cargo clippy stages set to 900s
    - a cold-worktree bot-merge of a Rust gap completes test+clippy stages without a mid-compile botmerge_wedged SIGTERM

- id: RESILIENT-134
  domain: RESILIENT
  title: "RESILIENT: run-fleet+test-fleet-auth-check auth probe uses removed 'claude --once' flag — false-fails, blocks all fleet relaunch"
  status: open
  priority: P1
  effort: m
  description: |
    run-fleet.sh line 448 and scripts/ci/test-fleet-auth-check.sh line 69 probe auth by running: claude --once ok. The --once flag was removed from the Claude CLI (now returns error: unknown option --once), so the probe ALWAYS exits non-zero and run-fleet aborts with auth-probe-failed regardless of valid credentials. This silently blocked ALL fleet relaunch for ~13h while auth was actually fine (claude -p works). Fix: replace claude --once with claude -p (verified working) in both files. Already applied locally to run-fleet.sh so the fleet is running now; needs committing to main plus the test file fixed.
  acceptance_criteria:
    - run-fleet.sh auth probe uses claude -p not --once
    - test-fleet-auth-check.sh uses claude -p not --once
    - a clean run-fleet launch with valid auth reaches auth-probe-succeeded and spawns workers
    - "regression: grep claude --once in scripts returns nothing"

- id: RESILIENT-135
  domain: RESILIENT
  title: "RESILIENT: worker.sh timeout death-spiral — INFRA-1160 effort-scaling mutates global FLEET_TIMEOUT_S, compounding xs gaps 1800→...→0s; every claude -p killed rc=124, autonomous completion ~0"
  status: done
  priority: P0
  effort: s
  description: |
    ROOT CAUSE of RESILIENT-131 (autonomous completion ~0), found by watching a live worker (chump-worker-3.log, 2026-06-08). worker.sh:851 'FLEET_TIMEOUT_S=$_scaled_timeout' overwrites the GLOBAL base timeout with the effort-scaled value. FLEET_TIMEOUT_S persists across the worker's cycle loop, so each cycle multiplies the ALREADY-scaled base by the effort fraction again. For repeated xs gaps (x0.5) it halves every cycle: 1800->...->14->7->3->1->0s. Downstream the claude -p spawn (worker.sh:864/866) and watchdog (876) read FLEET_TIMEOUT_S, so the implementation budget collapses to 0-7s. Every claude -p is killed (rc=124) before it can implement anything; a rescue commits an empty WIP; the worktree leaks. This is why ~14/15 recent ships are Opus-driven, not Sonnet workers. Base default (1800s) is fine — the mutation is the sole cause. Fix: keep FLEET_TIMEOUT_S immutable as the base (new FLEET_TIMEOUT_BASE_S), derive the per-cycle timeout from the base each cycle, add a floor so it can never collapse. Sibling bug (separate gap): worker.sh:703 mutates global FLEET_MODEL the same way (haiku sticks across cycles).
  acceptance_criteria:
    - worker.sh derives the per-cycle claude -p timeout from an IMMUTABLE base; running N consecutive xs gaps does NOT compound the multiplier (timeout stays at base*0.5, never 0).
    - A floor (CHUMP_WORKER_TIMEOUT_MIN_S, default >=120s) guarantees the scaled timeout can never collapse below a workable implementation budget.
    - "A BEHAVIORAL test (scripts/ci/test-worker-timeout-scale.sh) asserts: same base+effort yields the same result on repeated calls (non-compounding), effort multipliers (xs=0.5/s=1.0/m=1.5), max cap, and min floor — exercising the real scaling code, not a grep."
    - After ship + worker restart, a live worker spawns claude -p with a minutes-scale timeout (not 0-7s) and worker_timeout_no_commit rate drops.
  notes: |
    Fixed by #3109 (fix(RESILIENT-135): worker timeout death-spiral — per-cycle budget from immutable base), merged to main 7ad6a2c56. Stale-open P0 de-inflation 2026-06-20.
  closed_pr: 3109
  outcome_id: MISSION-010

- id: RESILIENT-136
  domain: RESILIENT
  title: "RESILIENT: worker.sh model-routing mutates global FLEET_MODEL across cycles (same anti-pattern as RESILIENT-135) — per-cycle resolved model sticks; haiku contaminates later sonnet cycles"
  status: open
  priority: P1
  effort: s
  description: |
    Sibling of RESILIENT-135 (same mutate-the-global-in-a-loop anti-pattern). worker.sh:712 (FLEET_MODEL=$_resolved_model from routing.yaml) and :726 (FLEET_MODEL=$_gap_required_model) assign to the GLOBAL FLEET_MODEL — but the comment at :701 explicitly says 'overriding FLEET_MODEL locally for the current cycle only.' FLEET_MODEL persists across the worker's cycle loop with no reset, so once any gap routes to haiku (routing.yaml or required_model), FLEET_MODEL=haiku STICKS for all subsequent cycles, including gaps that should use sonnet. Observed live 2026-06-08 (worker spawning model=haiku). Per INFRA-515, fleet workers should be sonnet (haiku hesitates in --dangerously-skip-permissions, burning the slot). Fix: keep FLEET_MODEL as the immutable base (e.g. FLEET_MODEL_BASE), resolve the per-cycle model into a LOCAL var used only for the spawn, never mutating the base — mirror the RESILIENT-135 FLEET_TIMEOUT_BASE_S fix.
  acceptance_criteria:
    - Per-cycle model resolution (routing.yaml + gap.required_model) uses a LOCAL variable for the spawn; the worker's base FLEET_MODEL is never mutated, so a haiku-routed gap does NOT change the model used by the next cycle.
    - "A behavioral test asserts: after resolving model=haiku for gap A, gap B with no routing still resolves to the base (sonnet) — i.e. no cross-cycle contamination."

- id: RESILIENT-137
  domain: RESILIENT
  title: "RESILIENT (Cut-Friction): streamline the commit-gate stack — a 60-line docs commit took 5 attempts (stomp-hang, net-new-docs, bypass-4-field, index-mutex pileup)"
  status: open
  priority: P1
  effort: m
  description: |
    Part of MISSION-044 (Cut the Friction). Landing a 60-line docs change (META-287) took FIVE commit attempts, each blocked by a different gate discovered one-at-a-time: (1) bare git commit hung on the stomp prompt (non-tty); (2) net-new-docs trailer required; (3) a preemptive Off-Rails-Bypass trailer triggered a 4-required-field bypass-validator; (4) the chump-commit index-mutex hard-failed after 30s under normal concurrency; (5) a zsh GID-var assignment attempted setgid. Each gate is individually reasonable but STACKED + non-fail-fast they make a trivial commit a multi-attempt slog.
  acceptance_criteria:
    - chump-commit emits ALL required trailers/remediation in ONE failure message (not one-per-retry)
    - stomp + any interactive gate is non-tty-safe (auto-default in headless, no hang)
    - a non-bypass commit never triggers the bypass-trailer 4-field validator
    - index-mutex contention degrades gracefully (clear retry, not hard 30s fail)
    - a 60-line docs change commits in ONE attempt

